<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Minorities forced to go to predatory lenders  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Minority homeowners are routinely turned down by
conventional banks at greater rates than whites with comparable
incomes, according to a study by U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer's
office.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, blacks and Hispanics are forced to go to
high-interest lenders who charge much more in interest and fees
than conventional lending institutions, Schumer said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The senator is calling on conventional banks to change the trend
and has introduced legislation to prohibit some of the unscrupulous
practices of the high-interest lenders.
</P>
<P>
   ''You could tell a tale of two cities when it comes to bank
lending,'' Schumer said. ''If you're white, it's easy to get a
conventional mortgage. If you're black at the same income level or
higher than a white family, it's next to impossible to get a
conventional mortgage. As a result, black homeowners must resort to
predatory lenders who have high-interest levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The study found, for example, that 20 percent of black families
making $60,000 were turned down by a conventional bank, compared
with 17 percent of white families making $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   The study analyzed data on nearly 240,000 1998 home loans and
refinance applications in New York City. The data were supplied to
the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development under the Home
Mortgage Disclosure Act.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's study did not account for the credit histories of
applicants, employment history or other factors that banks may
consider in their lending decisions.
</P>
<P>
   High-interest lenders -- also known as subprime lenders because
they make loans to people with less than stellar credit histories --
sometimes supply the money other banks won't.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them -- Champion, the Money Store and Delta -- are well
known in the New York area because they market their services
aggressively on television, on radio and by telephone, promising to
provide mortgages to anyone who's been rejected by a traditional
bank.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, who refer to them as predatory lenders, charge that
they also encourage people to borrow more than they can afford to
pay back so that they will default and enable the lender to
foreclose.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's study examined 12 neighborhoods of comparable median
incomes in the Bronx, Queens and Brooklyn, half of them
predominantly black and half mostly white. In the black areas, on
average, 26 percent of mortgage applicants were rejected for a loan
at a conventional bank, compared with 14 percent of applicants in
the six white neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's study showed that in predominantly black
neighborhoods, more than half of the mortgages were issued by
subprime lenders, compared with 13 percent in white neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has introduced the Predatory Lending Deterrence Act to
protect consumers by, among other things, prohibiting lenders from:
</P>
<P>
   -- Charging penalties for prepaying the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   -- Financing points and fees, for which conventional lenders
require up front payment.
</P>
<P>
   -- Using negative amortization, in which mortgage payments pay
off only interest instead of principal.
</P>
<P>
   -- Lending without regard to the borrower's ability to pay, which
leads to default and foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer is also sending the report to conventional banks, asking
them to take steps to remedy the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Gary R. Brody, vice president of the Community Bankers
Association of New York State, suggested that in some
neighborhoods, the trend could be explained not so much by the
failure of conventional banks to grant mortgages as by the heavy
marketing by the subprime lenders.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sometimes an occasion of the predatory lenders going in
there looking to make some business -- Delta and others -- and often
starting out as offers for home improvement loans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brody cautioned against jumping to the conclusion that ''the
reason these people are being victimized is that they have gone to
the bank and for some nefarious reason been turned down. Sometimes
the lender of last resort has jumped the gun on the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   He said some practices outlawed by Schumer's proposal are
already illegal in New York, such as penalties for prepaying a
mortgage. Others would become illegal here under regulations
proposed and soon to be adopted by the state Banking Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
