<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Visit Univ. of Arkansas  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- President Clinton and the first lady
rekindled special memories with two of their oldest and dearest
friends during a weekend visit to the University of Arkansas -- the
campus where both Clintons taught law a quarter century ago.
</P>
<P>
   The president and his wife, Hillary, spent the afternoon and
evening Sunday with James and Diane Blair, who have been among
their closest companions since the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Blair left the university faculty, where she was a
political science professor for two decades, last fall because of
illness. She suffers from terminal cancer. James Blair is a
prominent lawyer in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Friends for nearly 30 years, the Clintons and Blairs frequently
keep in touch by telephone. Often when they return to Arkansas, the
Clintons visit the Blairs in this college town or at the Blair's
vacation home at Beaver Lake.
</P>
<P>
   This trip was marked by added emotion, however, because of Mrs.
Blair's illness.
</P>
<P>
   ''They wanted to take this opportunity to spend some time with
her,'' said White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by the Blairs, the president, first lady and
daughter Chelsea took a meandering motor trip through town and the
university campus. Later the Clintons had dinner and remained until
late in the evening at the Blair's home outside Fayetteville.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's friendship with the Blairs dates back to her
arrival in the state in the 1970s. Clinton, as a young governor,
gave the vows at the Blair's wedding. When the Clintons were
married, they had the reception in the backyard of the Blair's
home.
</P>
<P>
   During their days in Arkansas, the young Clinton couple would
turn to the Blairs for political advice.
</P>
<P>
   In the '70s, Jim Blair already was one of the state's most
prominent trial lawyers. Later he became general counsel for Tyson
Foods Inc., one of the state's most powerful businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's friendship with Mrs. Clinton brought headlines when it
was learned that he had suggested she invest money in the
commodities market. She did, and turned a $1,000 investment in
cattle futures into a $100,000 bonanza in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was on a streak that I thought was very successful and I
wanted to share this with my close friends,'' Blair once told an
interviewer, describing Mrs. Clinton as ''the best person at my
marriage ... a tennis partner and friend.''
</P>
<P>
   During the campus tour, the Clintons and Blairs stopped in front
of the law school, where a brass plaque commemorates the
president's and first lady's days on the faculty. He began teaching
there in 1973, she in 1974. Both departed when Clinton became state
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clintons on Law Faculty,'' reads an inscription on the plaque,
which also notes that Mrs. Clinton founded a legal clinic there.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a nice surprise,'' Mrs. Clinton said. It was the first
time the Clintons had seen the plaque.
</P>
<P>
   Then along with the Blairs it was on to a ''peace fountain''
dedicated to former Arkansas Sen. J. William Fulbright, for whom
Clinton once briefly worked on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street is the university's main building, one that
holds special memories for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ''Back in my former life, we restored it,'' Clinton remarked,
noting that the ''Old Maine'' building was built in 1871 during the
Reconstruction Era following the Civil War. Its north tower is
taller than the south one, he pointed out. When Clinton was
governor some people in the state wanted to tear the building down,
but he intervened.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's such a beautiful building. ... I don't like tearing
things down,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
