<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PM-NY--Hizzoner and the Cops, Bjt,1010  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It would be hard to find a bigger booster of the
New York City Police than Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. Even in difficult
cases -- like the much-publicized recent killings of unarmed black
men by undercover officers -- the mayor always stands by the police.
</P>
<P>
   But not all New York cops are happy with the mayor's outspoken
support.
</P>
<P>
   Some complain that his tough rhetoric on crime makes their jobs
more difficult. Others say Giuliani, who is running for the U.S.
Senate against first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, is involving them
in politics. Still others feel the mayor's campaigns against the
smallest crimes -- jaywalking or drinking in public -- bring derision
to the police.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's trying to show the voters upstate he's tough on crime,
but he has us running around arresting people for silly violations,
like spitting on the sidewalk,'' said a Manhattan officer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Would he shut up so we can do our job?'' laments a Queens
police captain. ''He's taken things that shouldn't be
confrontational and made them confrontational.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments were typical of 30 New York police interviewed in
the past week, all of whom insisted their names not be used for
fear of retribution. But police union officials and experts speak
openly of the growing annoyance by police over Giuliani's policies
-- though some say the anger grows from low police wages or simply
the mayor's absolute control of the nation's largest police
department, with about 41,000 officers, which once prided itself on
its independence.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very well known, within the department and by the public,
that the mayor has taken total control of the Police Department,''
said Thomas Scotto, president of the Detectives Endowment
Association. ''When you have politicians running the Police
Department, rather than the knowledgeable people within the
department, you are bound to have problems. That's precisely what
is happening right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The last straw for many officers was Giuliani's response after
Patrick Dorismond, an unarmed security guard, was shot to death in
a confrontation with narcotics officers last month.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dorismond, the son of Haitian immigrants, was never
convicted of a crime, the mayor ordered police to release his
record of arrests -- including some sealed records of juvenile
offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Outrage followed among the Haitian community, and some others,
and people vented their anger at protests. The tension escalated at
Dorismond's funeral in Brooklyn, when a melee broke out between
mourners and police, resulting in injuries on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Several police officials say the shooting badly hurt morale --
which already was at an alltime low because of meager wages
compared to suburban police and the bad publicity over the police
torture of Abner Louima and the fatal shooting of black immigrant
Amadou Diallo by four white officers.
</P>
<P>
   To counter the bad press, the unions representing police
lieutenants and captains took out a full-page ad in the New York
Post recently. ''New York City Police Officers Do Care'' was the
message.
</P>
<P>
   ''Regardless of what anybody says, police officers day in and
day out are going out on patrol and risking their lives for the
residents of the city of New York,'' said Capt. John Driscoll,
president of the Captains Endowment Association.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Garvey, president of the Lieutenants Benevolent
Association, said the ad was needed to cut through all the
political rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're in the political season and the volume is turned up so
high and no one is listening to the facts,'' he said. ''There are a
couple of highlighted media cases that people capitalize on, and
they turn those cases into the norm. We needed to get the facts out
to the people.''
</P>
<P>
   The stress of the job, low morale and frustration is evident in
the exodus of cops retiring from the force. Last year, 888 officers
retired when they reached 20 years of service, compared with 617 in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   One Manhattan officer said the public unhappiness with police is
partly tied to Giuliani. She said she appreciates it when he stands
by the police, but added: ''People in the minority communities hate
him so much, so when he sticks up for us, that makes them hate us
as well. A lot of cops are frustrated, especially those of us on
the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   The public's mistrust of police has puzzled several experts who
say the people ought to be praising cops in these times. Crime is
at an all-time low, and fatal police shootings of civilians are
down from 41 in 1990 to 11 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Police killings are down 75 percent and we're in the middle of
a kind of political hysteria,'' said Fred Siegel, an urban affairs
specialist and history professor at Cooper Union. ''Usually if
police killings drop more than crime, it would be thought of as an
enormous accomplishment. But it's not now, because we're in the
middle of a political season.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel was critical of the mayor's handling of the Dorismond
case, but said he believes most police still have a positive
attitude toward the mayor. He added that Giuliani's critics are
using the Dorismond case -- and the police -- against him, a tried
and true method in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ''Racial incidents are used to polarize people -- it's how
incumbents are driven out of office here,'' Siegel said, referring
to racial or ethnic controversies that are believed to have helped
defeat former mayors Ed Koch and David Dinkins.
</P>
<P>
   Gene O'Donnell, a former NYPD officer who teaches at John Jay
College of Criminal Justice, doesn't think the mayor has cops
frustrated -- rather, it's low wages and relationships with their
bosses. Several police officers agreed, including one who said he
rarely thinks about the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   But one Manhattan detective said the city needs a mayor whose
politics are less tied to the police department.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now we're in this situation -- we're damned if we do
something, and damned if we don't,'' he said. ''It bothers me --
this is going to be a long, tough summer.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
