<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer moms who supported Bill Clinton are wary of Hillary  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCARSDALE, N.Y. (AP) -- They helped Bill Clinton score a goal in
'96. But soccer moms in the suburbs that Hillary Clinton now calls
home aren't cheering for her Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I always vote Democrat, but I am not committed to Hillary,''
said Gerri Jaffe as she watched her daughter's team chase a ball
across a field in Scarsdale, a short drive from the Clintons'
Chappaqua home. ''We have some very good Democratic politicians who
could have been the candidate for Senate, but it was given to
her.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I like her as a first lady, I like her very much,'' said
Maryann Mancino, of Larchmont, who works in a family owned clothing
business, as she cheered her daughter's team at a nearby stadium in
Mamaroneck. ''I think she's smart and very focused, but I don't
think she's right for New York state.''
</P>
<P>
   Most polls show that among all voters, support for Giuliani and
Clinton is about even, with the mayor's standing slipping after his
handling of the case of Patrick Dorismond, an unarmed black man
shot by police. But among suburban voters and white women, the
mayor has led the first lady by a ratio of roughly 5 to 3 for
months.
</P>
<P>
   The gap is contrary to what might be expected. After all, New
York's suburban voters picked Bill Clinton over Bob Dole nearly 2
to 1, and Hillary Clinton is not unlike the women whose votes elude
her -- an educated, middle-class, working mother whose top issues
are education and health.
</P>
<P>
   And just like them, she rejected fabulous Manhattan and bucolic
upstate for a nice big house on a tree-lined street in the land of
Ford Explorers and golden retrievers.
</P>
<P>
   But the soccer moms aren't impressed by the Chappaqua address.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm appalled she's even running,'' said Marjorie Sagiv, a
mother of two and owner of a small import-export business. ''She
came out of no place. She's not even a New Yorker. It's a
travesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though she's practically your neighbor?
</P>
<P>
   ''Especially because she's my neighbor,'' said Sagiv. ''Who does
she think she is? She's the president's wife. But that doesn't give
her a right to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Many suburbanites also credit Giuliani with making New York City
cleaner and safer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I lived in New York City for eight years. I see a tremendous
change from his efforts there,'' said Monique Gotkin, of Scarsdale,
as she watched her daughter's team, the Wildcats, play in nearby
Mamaroneck.
</P>
<P>
   As for Hillary Clinton, she added, ''I don't see how she's going
to improve things here.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokesman Howard Wolfson predicts that as female
voters get to know her, ''you're going to see a movement in the
polls among that group. One of the things that is key is for people
to know what Hillary did before she entered the White House. A lot
of people just don't know, for instance, that she was the first
female law partner in her law firm. They don't know that she was
named one of America's top 100 lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   One new poll showed women may be getting Wolfson's message. It
had Clinton and Giuliani statistically tied among white women;
still Giuliani remained ahead about 5 to 4 among suburbanites in
general.
</P>
<P>
   Even soccer moms who think highly of Clinton may not want her in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I admire her but I probably won't vote for her,'' said Monica
Rafajac, a former attorney and Scarsdale mother of two. ''With
Giuliani, you either hate him or you feel like he follows through.
He can be obnoxious, but his heart is in the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are less impressed by Clinton's record.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see what she's done as first lady to get her husband's
ear on poverty, children, women,'' said Stacey Tecklin, an attorney
from Harrison with two children. ''I will give her credit as a
mother -- her daughter seems wonderful. But I think she should have
started out a little bit smaller'' in her political goals.
</P>
<P>
   As for Giuliani, Tecklin said, ''I'm not happy with his handling
of the police shooting (of Dorismond), but I will still support him
wholeheartedly. I think he really turned around the city. He's a
leader, not a follower.''
</P>
<P>
   After the fatal shooting last month, Giuliani pictured Dorismond
as a violent man, released sealed records of his juvenile crimes
and did not express condolences to his family. Clinton and many
others criticized the mayor's behavior as racially divisive.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also has some critics in the soccer-mom set.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's crazy and that he's a fascist,'' said Ann
Helpern, of Harrison, a mother of three. ''(Clinton's lack of New
York roots) doesn't bother me. The breadth of her experience, her
intelligence -- she's so thoughtful. And she cares about the issues
that are important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Most polls have shown about 10 percent of voters are undecided,
and many soccer moms have questions about both Clinton and
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think she says enough about what she really stands
for, and when she does speak, she says what she thinks we want to
hear,'' said Susan Peck, a bookkeeper from Mamaroneck with three
children. ''I think he's done a great job in the city, but he
really is city-based and I don't really know how he feels about
statewide issues.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ''I'm a Democrat, but I'm not wedded to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
