<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 02:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eat an Orange, Banish a Gallstone?  </HEADLINE>
By LINDSEY TANNER, AP Medical Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- An orange a day could keep the gallbladder doctor
away.
</P>
<P>
   A new study of 13,130 men and women suggests that women who
don't get enough vitamin C may be prone to gallbladder disease.
</P>
<P>
   Though the study doesn't say vitamin C can prevent gallbladder
disease, it ''supports that hypothesis,'' said Dr. Joel Simon, the
lead author and an assistant professor of medicine and epidemiology
at the University of California-San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The findings appear in Monday's Archives of Internal Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller studies have found a similar association, and research
has shown that vitamin C-deficient guinea pigs frequently develop
gallstones. Simon theorized that the same might be true in humans.
</P>
<P>
   Gallstones can form when bile, a liquid produced by the liver to
help break down fats during digestion, becomes oversaturated with
cholesterol. Animal studies have shown vitamin C regulates the
conversion of cholesterol into bile acids, Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hypothesized that low levels of vitamin C may be a risk
factor for human gallbladder disease as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The gallbladder is a pear-shaped sac beneath the liver where
bile is stored. Disease is frequently characterized by gallstones,
which can grow up to an inch across and cause severe abdominal
pain. Treatment may involve removal of the gallbladder.
</P>
<P>
   Of the estimated 19 million Americans with gallbladder disease,
two-thirds are women, Simon said. Women are believed to be more
prone because the feminine hormone estrogen increases the
concentration of cholesterol in the bile, and most gallstones are
made of cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Simon examined data on participants in a national health and
nutrition survey conducted between 1988 and 1994. Low bloodstream
levels of ascorbic acid -- vitamin C's chemical name -- were
associated with an increased prevalence of symptomatic gallbladder
disease in women, but not men.
</P>
<P>
   Women with higher ascorbic acid levels and those who took
vitamin C supplements were significantly less likely to have the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Though no vitamin C link was noted in the men, Simon said that
may be simply because there wasn't enough gallbladder disease in
men to detect a statistical association.
</P>
<P>
   More research is needed to examine how men might be affected and
to determine if vitamin C does in fact have preventive powers,
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Archives of Internal Medicine site: http://archinte.ama-assn.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-10-00 0258 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000410.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain praises Giuliani as independent-minded  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD PYLE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Sen. John McCain ridiculed Hillary Rodham
Clinton's charge that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is in the pocket of
right-wing zealots but joked that he himself is proud to be part of
the ''vast right-wing conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Its members, he said with a laugh, might even help Giuliani win
his U.S. Senate campaign against the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure that will be sufficient to put us over the top and
eliminate any further need for fund-raising and further
campaigning,'' the former presidential candidate cracked Sunday at
a joint news conference with Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting Long Island to endorse a GOP House candidate, the
Arizona senator stopped in Manhattan to meet with Giuliani at a
midtown restaurant, where he called the suggestion that Giuliani is
allied with the far right ''ludicrous on the face of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He praised the mayor as an independent-minded politician who, if
elected, would ''speak for those that many times in the halls of
the United States Senate are not spoken for.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He has proven as mayor of this great city that he not only can
make the streets safe but help the people of New York and the
United States realize the American dream,'' McCain said. ''I
believe what's needed in Washington is a person who will speak up
for all Americans regardless of party affiliation, and I am
convinced that not only is he not a captive of any special
interest, he will be a voice for the people of Arizona as well as
the people of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit came as Giuliani's campaign aired a new 30-second
television ad linking him to the Arizona senator. McCain won
widespread acclaim, if not sufficient voter support, in his
maverick primary bid for the White House. In the ad, Giuliani says
he shares McCain's independent approach to public issues.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Post item, quoting Clinton media consultant Ellis
Verdi as expressing surprise that Giuliani ''would associate
himself with someone (McCain) who is that far to the right,'' was
displayed on a placard as the two shared coffee and chitchat then
met with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I notice that after my last visit here that I am now part of
the vast right-wing conspiracy,'' McCain said. ''I am very proud to
be part of that organization. Obviously I received a groundswell of
their support in the campaign that I just completed unsuccessfully.
As a member of the vast right-wing conspiracy I attach myself to
this campaign, and I seek all of you to examine our tenets and our
philosophies.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the hastily arranged meeting was to show that
''I'm not going to be deterred by comments from the other side, and
that I'm very proud to be associated with John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain added: ''Not only are we friends, but we seized this
opportunity to hatch several plots to take over the government in
the hope that one of them will succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used the term ''vast right-wing conspiracy'' in a 1998
television interview to describe a purported campaign by
well-financed groups and individuals to discredit President Clinton
and herself.
</P>
<P>
   Her senate campaign spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said she has
never called Giuliani or McCain part of the alleged conspiracy but
simply pointed out that the mayor's campaign has accepted
contributions from fund-raisers identified with ultraconservative
causes.
</P>
<P>
   ''John McCain is not running for the Senate, Rudy Giuliani is,
and at some point Giuliani is going to have to tell the people of
New York where he stands on the issues,'' Wolfson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
