<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 04:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Convicted Marine Capt. Reprimanded  </HEADLINE>
By RANDALL CHASE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A court-martialed Marine captain who
faces an uncertain military future says he is haunted by memories
of a reservist who died following a grueling training hike he
supervised.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not a day goes by that I don't think about him,'' Capt. Victor
Arana said, reading from a prepared statement, as relatives of
Lance Cpl. Giuseppe ''Joey'' Leto sobbed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would do or give anything to be able to bring him back. Many
nights I have lain awake haunted by the memories of my own
inactions during the march on July 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Arana, 28, of Chicago, was found guilty of dereliction of duty
and failure to obey an order in the death of 21-year-old Leto, of
New Milford, Conn. He was reprimanded Sunday and was ordered to
forfeit $3,600 in pay.
</P>
<P>
   Leto was found dead of heat stroke two hours after the 8-mile
hike -- conducted at night in 80-degree heat -- following a head
count that prompted a search for him.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Ralph Kohlmann, the military judge who found Arana
guilty on Saturday, could have sentenced him to nine months in
prison and dismissed him from the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's obviously relieved, and he's going to go home and spend
some time with his wife,'' said Arana's civilian attorney, Mark
Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Pleading for leniency, Stevens told the judge Arana's career as
a Marine officer is finished. ''His promotion has been taken away.
He has a federal conviction that will follow him the rest of his
life,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   After the sentencing, Stevens said he expects Arana to resign
when his current service term ends in December, if not before. He
said Arana will report back to duty this week, not in a command
position, but in an administrative post at the Marine Corps Combat
Services Support Schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''He will not be in charge of any other Marines,'' said Leto's
mother, Domenica. ''He will be pushing papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Arana led the hike at a faster pace than the
2{-mile-per-hour pace prescribed by training guidelines and didn't
allow enough rest breaks. Witnesses also said Arana went home
before a head count was completed.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Maj. Chris Hamilton, asked the judge to dismiss
Arana from the Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   ''The accused does not deserve to wear the uniform and the rank
of an officer of the Marines,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys argued that Arana, a rookie company commander
still drawing his lieutenant's pay while wearing captain's bars,
did not receive proper instructions from his superiors. They also
said Arana's noncommissioned officers failed to communicate with
him or follow his orders for taking care of stragglers.
</P>
<P>
   While Arana made errors in judgment and leadership and was
willing to take responsibility for his mistakes, others were to
blame for Leto's death as well, Stevens argued.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a general failure,'' he told the judge. ''There was
a failure at the School of Infantry, there was a failure by his
staff; and he stands alone at this court-martial to pay the
ultimate price.''
</P>
<P>
   Camp Lejeune tightened and revised training in standard
operating procedures for new infantry instructors following Leto's
death. They also created two new positions for inspectors to
monitor infantry school training.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.lejeune.usmc.mil
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
