<HEADLINE> Ivanov Reassures Business Leaders  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov told a gathering of
U.S. and Western businessmen Monday that Russia will adopt a new
tax code and strive to protect investors' rights, a ministry
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The comments came as newly elected President Vladimir Putin
strives to convince foreign investors that his administration will
offer stability and opportunity following the chaotic years of his
predecessor, Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov said Russia's the new leadership ''is creating favorable
conditions for the expansion of economic ties with Western
partners, particularly in the sphere of investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign direct investment in Russia remains tiny compared to the
country's size, reaching just $4.26 billion last year. That figure
could rise if Putin carries out so far vague promises of reform,
analysts have said. A detailed economic program is expected on May
7, Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov told potential investors the new leadership planned to
pass long-stalled land and tax reform legislation, and hinted at
business-friendly policies while also improving social welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly, for foreign partners and investors, the domestic
political situation and stability have important meaning,'' he
said. ''We are confident that from this point of view our
cooperation has great prospects.''
</P>
</TEXT>
