<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 09:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Submarine force celebrates its centennial  </HEADLINE>
sdnldnorsy
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROTON, Conn. (AP) -- The U.S. Navy bought its first submarine on
April 11, 1900 from Electric Boat, tying the Groton shipyard and
southeastern Connecticut's fortunes to the fleet for most of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the submarine force marks its centennial, it is
celebrating its history and its future. The official observances
began Sunday in Groton, with a memorial service conducted by the
U.S. Submarine Veterans.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony included a Tolling of the Boats, during which a
ship's bell was tolled for each submarine lost during the past
century.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Smithsonian Institution will open its $2
million tribute to submarining, featuring parts from three
decommissioned subs, the Trepang and the Sand Lance, which had
their last homeport in Groton, and the James K. Polk.
</P>
<P>
   On April 28, the repository of the fleet's heritage, the
Submarine Force Library and Museum in Groton, will formally open
its new $4 million expansion, designed to better display some of
the 23,000 artifacts and 35,000 photographs and the world's largest
submarine library.
</P>
<P>
   The submarine that started it all, the USS Holland, would hardly
be recognizable by today's standards. It was just over 53 feet long
and a little more than 10 feet in diameter, powered by a gasoline
motor on the surface and a combination of batteries and electric
motors when submerged. It never made more than 10 knots.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Navy's newest sub, the Seawolf, is 300 feet
longer and 160 times heavier. These subs roam the seven seas with
impunity.
</P>
<P>
   But the first subs were limited to the East Coast and primarily
to harbor defense. A decade later, they were sent to the Pacific
but during World War I saw only limited action, primarily on
anti-U-Boat patrols in Ireland and the Azores. During that time,
however, the Groton sub base expanded greatly, with 81 new
buildings, nine finger piers and extensive waterfront construction.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1930s, with war again looming, Electric Boat was
turning out three subs a year. By 1944, during the height of the
Second World War, EB was able to turn out 23 subs a year.
</P>
<P>
   It was during WWII that subs proved their worth. With the
Pacific surface fleet in ruins at Pearl Harbor, it fell to the
submariners to take the fight to the invading Japanese Fleet. Three
days after the attack, the USS Triton carried out the first torpedo
attack on the Japanese Navy south of Wake Island.
</P>
<P>
   Before the war was over, submarines sank 214 naval ships and
1,113 merchant vessels, effectively cutting off Japan's supply
routes.
</P>
<P>
   But the so-called Silent Service had its own losses: 52 subs and
3,500 submariners during WWII.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. H.A. Lincoln Jr., commanding officer of the Groton Naval
Submarine Base, said it's essential that people know of the
tremendous contributions made by submarines and the sacrifices made
by their crews.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's important that we not lose this tie, this
connection, to our past,'' Lincoln said. ''We stand on the
foundation that they built for us, and I feel we should never, ever
lose sight of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-10-00 0945 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
