<HEADLINE> Dow Up 43.98; Nasdaq Down 50.75  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed at the start of trading today,
with technology shares heading lower as investors wondered whether
first-quarter earnings reports will justify tech stocks' high
prices.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 43.98 at 11,155.46.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were modestly lower. The Nasdaq
composite index was down 50.75 at 4,395.70, and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was down 2.32 to 1,514.03.
</P>
<P>
   Technology shares, still vulnerable after last week's wild
gyrations, led the decliners. Microsoft fell 2 1/16 to 87, and
Applied Materials lost 2} to 112[ on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are waiting to see whether earnings reports for the
recently ended first quarter will show the rapid growth that
convinced many people to bid technology stocks to unprecedented
levels earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology company Amgen and chip maker Motorola were
scheduled to report earnings today, with Advanced Micro Devices and
Rambus to follow on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate profits are generally expected to be quite strong for
the first quarter. Analysts expect technology and energy companies
to show the biggest improvement from the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow rose on the strength of American Express, up 1 13/16 to
140~.
</P>
<P>
   Advancers outnumbered decliners by a few dozen issues on the New
York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 109.25 million shares,
well behind Friday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 2.34 to 540.65.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.8 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.8 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.9 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
up 1.7 percent.
</P>
