<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forget that April showers stuff: Winter storm wallops state  </HEADLINE>
With AP Photo
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Eastern New York residents today are
wondering what happened to spring.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend storm that rolled in from the Plains brought
2-inch-per hour snow on Sunday morning and gusty winds of up to 15
mph in the afternoon. At the Albany International Airport control
tower Saturday afternoon, temperatures dropped 14 degrees in less
than 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   David Skoczylas of Terryville, Conn., on Sunday said,
''yesterday it was 70 degrees and we were playing golf. Today we're
stuck in a winter storm. I brought my golf shoes but I should have
brought my boots.''
</P>
<P>
   Slick roads forced Skoczylas to extend his visit with family and
friends until today.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern and northern New York got most of the snow. The Albany
area received at least 12 inches, with communities to the north or
in higher elevations getting more.
</P>
<P>
   Tree limbs sagged under the weight of the wet snow, snapping off
onto power lines and knocking out electricity for more than 30,000
Niagara Mohawk customers, most of them in Saratoga County.
</P>
<P>
   Between 3,000 and 4,000 customers were still without power
Sunday night, but Niagara Mohawk spokesman Nick Lyman said power
was expected to return to all customers before the end of today.
</P>
<P>
   Much of western New York had just a dusting or little
accumulation. Rochester and Buffalo had less than an inch while the
Southern Tier town of Sanford near Binghamton had 7.5 inches by
dawn and Chenango Forks in Chenango County had almost 7 inches. But
the storm was spotty, dropping as little 2 inches of snow a few
dozen miles from where a town was socked with 6 or 7 inches.
</P>
<P>
   The storm caused several accidents on eastern New York roads. In
Columbia County, a Fort Drum soldier lost both his legs when he was
struck by several vehicles while assisting stranded motorists on
the Thruway.
</P>
<P>
   State police say 23-year-old Dean Johnson of Warwick, R.I., was
injured when a car carrier jackknifed on a bridge and plunged over
the side. Johnson is listed in serious condition at Albany Medical
Center, where the truck drive is listed as fair.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend storm also played havoc with events.
</P>
<P>
   Mark DeNofio, special events director of a multi-county
walk-athon to benefit Multiple Sclerosis, had to cancel the major
fund-raising event. A local telethon to benefit the Arthritis
Foundation was also touched by the snow that made for tough
slogging and threatened power for the second day of the two-day
event in Niskayuna, outside Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The Rochester Red Wings minor league baseball games against
Scranton Wilkes-Barre were canceled Saturday because of rain and on
Sunday because of snow. Other baseball games from the Binghamton
Mets in the minor leagues to the New York Mets in the majors were
also canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ''It hit us quick,'' said R.C. Reuteman, vice president and
general manager of the Eastern League Binghamton Mets, which
suspended a tie game against the Norwich Navigators in the top of
the sixth inning before 1,827 fans. ''We were able to get a tarp
out, but the National Weather Service said it wasn't going to let
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the storm was far from a record. The record for an April
snow storm is 17.7 inches, set in 1982, one year after 14.7 inches
was recorded in April, according to the National Weather Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
