<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army MD Charged With Manslaughter  </HEADLINE>
By GREG TOPPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MEADE, Md. (AP) -- An Army anesthesiologist charged with
involuntary manslaughter in the death of a 16-year-old girl may not
have been told that the antibiotic he administered could cause
someone's heart to stop in rare cases, a fellow doctor says.
</P>
<P>
   The Army alleges that Dr. Michael Hamner gave Katie Tyra a
massive dose of clindamycin and failed to call promptly for
assistance when she went into cardiac arrest during minor surgery
at Walter Reed Army Medical Center in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Two Army anesthesiologists offered different views on Hamner's
actions Sunday, the first day of a preliminary hearing that will
determine whether he will face a court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   A surgeon was to remove a small cyst on the Virginia girl's
neck, but she went into cardiac arrest, and attempts to revive her
failed. Katie never regained consciousness and died two weeks
later.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey Sagel, a staff anesthesiologist at Walter Reed, said
Hamner, a third-year resident in 1998, kept an incomplete record of
the drugs he administered. Sagel noted that Hamner, 35, also used
too much anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   ''Something's wrong -- something's very wrong,'' Sagel said as he
looked at Hamner's record of the procedure. ''Something caused this
heart rate to climb.''
</P>
<P>
   Sagel said a large dose of the antibiotic may have made the
girl's heart stop, noting that an allergic reaction to the drug
could have had the same effect.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Mark Kline, a former Walter Reed anesthesiologist who
reviewed the case for the Army, said the ''rare'' side effect was
not widely discussed and that he had never been told about it as a
resident.
</P>
<P>
   Hamner, Kline said, would never have given the massive dose of
clindamycin if he had known it could cause the heart to stop,
calling him ''a very careful resident, more careful than most.''
</P>
<P>
   The surgeon performing the operation had directed that Katie be
given clindamycin to guard against infection. Physicians generally
don't give patients more than 30 milligrams per minute, but Hamner
intravenously administered 900 mg of in less than two minutes.
Kline suggested he may have been rushed by demanding surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he felt he had to get the drug administered before
they got started,'' Kline said.
</P>
<P>
   After the girl went into cardiac arrest, Hamner tried to revive
her, then called for help from his supervisors, saying he didn't
know what had caused the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Hamner is the first Army doctor charged with involuntary
manslaughter due to malpractice in at least three decades, Pentagon
officials said. If the case goes to court-martial and he is
convicted on all counts, he could be sentenced to 30{ years in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing, which is similar to a civilian grand jury
proceeding, came after a two-year push by Katie's father, retired
Marine Corps Col. William D. Tyra, for an investigation into her
death.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter six months after Katie died, Hamner acknowledged
that he lied about how he administered the antibiotic. Despite
Hamner's admission, the Army allowed him to continue working as an
anesthesiologist in military hospitals. He was also slated for a
promotion until the girl's father protested. Hamner was later
assigned to administrative duties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
