<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 134; Nasdaq Down 46  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with technology shares
heading lower as investors wondered whether first-quarter earnings
reports will justify their high prices.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 134.65 at 11,246.13. Financial shares led the
advance after a Merrill Lynch strategist recommended clients move
some money from technology stocks into financials. American Express
rose 4 7/16 to 143{ and J.P. Morgan rose 5 9/16 to 135 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
was down 46.58 at 4,399.87, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
up 4.81 to 1,521.16.
</P>
<P>
   Technology shares, still vulnerable after last week's wild
gyrations, led the decliners. Microsoft fell 2 3/16 to 86~, and
Applied Materials lost 2] to 112{ on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are waiting to see whether earnings reports for the
recently ended first quarter will show the rapid growth that
convinced many people to bid technology stocks to unprecedented
levels earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology company Amgen and chip maker Motorola were
scheduled to report earnings today, with Advanced Micro Devices and
Rambus to follow on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''First-quarter earnings should be good and include some
positive surprises,'' said Gail Dudack, chief investment strategist
at Warburg Dillon Read in New York. She said the biggest surprises
-- companies that easily exceed analysts' published forecasts --
should come from the old-line energy and utility industries.
</P>
<P>
   A similar vote of confidence came from Richard McCabe, chief
market analyst at Merrill Lynch. McCabe told clients today that
they should reduce their exposure to technology stocks in favor of
energy, financial and consumer cyclical shares.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont rose 2 5/16 to 57 5/16, helping pull the Dow higher.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 268.00 million
shares, well behind Friday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 3.58 to 539.41.
</P>
<P>
