<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Dampens Grain, Soybean Prices  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean prices fell sharply today in
early dealings on the Chicago Board of Trade as investors pulled
back after a wet weekend throughout the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans tumbled after precipitation turned out to be more than
expected in the eastern soybean belt -- prime growing states.
Forecasts for scattered showers in the Midwest over the next two
days also added to the selling mood as drought fears continue to
subside.
</P>
<P>
   Also pressuring the soybean market were rumors that part of a
Chinese purchase of U.S. soybeans -- initial word of which drove
prices higher on Friday -- were South American soybeans instead.
</P>
<P>
   Weather also sent wheat prices significantly lower today. The
cold snap that enveloped the winter wheat belt over the weekend was
not severe enough to have caused crop damage, as some buyers had
thought.
</P>
<P>
   Corn futures took an early hit from the forecasts for more wet
weather, in addition to weekend precipitation. But the losses were
quickly wiped out amid a lack of selling interest.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery fell 4\ cents to $2.66} a bushel; May
corn was unchanged at $2.27 a bushel; May oats fell { cent to
$1.19\ a bushel; May soybeans fell 7\ cents to $5.31{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures advanced in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle rose .05 cent to 69.15 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle rose .30 cent to 84.30 cents a pound; June lean hogs
rose .50 cent to 74.50 cents a pound; May pork bellies rose .08
cent to 96.50 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
