<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children upbraid dad for killing mom  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- The children of a woman shot to death in
1998 pulled no punches when it came time to sentence the killer --
the father of two of the three youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   A judge Friday sentenced Tymus Ford Sr. to 37 years in prison
for killed killing Juanita Moore as she napped in their New Haven
home.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why did you take the best thing in our life?'' 8-year-old
Tymus Ford Jr. asked his father before the sentencing. ''We needed
our mother.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Ford pleaded guilty in January to killing Moore. He
said he murdered her because she had told him she was leaving him.
</P>
<P>
   Moore left three children: Tymus Jr., 4-year-old Amos, and
15-year-old Lyndell Moore, a child by a previous union.
</P>
<P>
   After Tymus Jr. addressed his father, Lyndell Moore also spoke
to Ford, who kept his eyes riveted on the floor for most of the
lengthy sentencing hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Moore told the man who had killed his mother, ''When I was
little, you told me to look people in the eye. Give me that
respect. You can't, because you're not man enough.''
</P>
<P>
   He also mentioned a crucifix Ford was wearing on a chain around
his neck. ''You should have had that cross when you took my
mother,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   The victim's brother, also named Lyndell Moore, called Ford a
coward ''who did a selfish act.''
</P>
<P>
   The victim's mother also spoke. She told the judge about her
struggle to raise her grandchildren who she said tend to blame
themselves for their mother's death. She told of Mother's Day
observances around a tombstone.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's mother, Mary Ford Wilton, then told the court how painful
it was not to be able to see her grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hurt as well,'' she said. ''I loved Juanita also. She was
like a daughter to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 40, held his head down, looking up only when his mother
spoke and when he told the judge, ''If I could take it back, I
would take it back. I'm very, very sorry for what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford's attorney, Richard Silverstein, said his client was
undergoing extreme emotional stress at the time of the killing. He
said Ford felt hopeless because he was out of work and unable to
provide for his family.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think everyone has a breaking point, people do, and when
they reach that point they often do things that have a devastating
effect. You can ruin your life and the life of another in an
instant ...''
</P>
<P>
   Silverstein said Ford did not expect forgiveness from his own or
Moore's family, adding, ''Maybe he'll never even forgive himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
