<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family hoped for more punishment, content with guilty verdict  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW MILFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Relatives of Giuseppe ''Joey'' Leto
wanted Marine Capt. Victor Arana thrown out of the service for his
role in the Connecticut reservist's death on a training hike.
</P>
<P>
   But they will accept the reprimand and order to forfeit pay
handed down to the man they blame for Joey's death.
</P>
<P>
   ''The guilty verdict was the most important thing to us. Now
(Arana) will never supervise other Marines. He'll be at a desk,
pushing papers, as an almost-captain,'' the dead Marine's mother,
Domenica Leto, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Arana, found guilty of dereliction of duty and failure to obey
an order, received the reprimand Sunday and was ordered to forfeit
$3,600 in pay.
</P>
<P>
   Arana, 28, of Chicago was charged in the death of Leto, 21, a
lance corporal from New Milford, Conn. He died after an 8-mile
night conditioning hike last July in 80-degree heat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know Joey paid the price with his life, and we hope his
death will not go in vain,'' Rosalia DesBiens, Joey Leto's aunt
said.
</P>
<P>
   After Leto's death, the Marines took several steps to improve
how hikes are conducted, such as ensuring supervisors are trained
properly.
</P>
<P>
   Leto's family wanted Arana dismissed from the Marines, but said
the reprimand and the conviction will get the same result.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there is some type of closure,'' said DesBiens, Joey's
aunt. ''We will go on. ... We have to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he was sentenced, Arana stood and read a prepared
statement asking for forgiveness from Leto's family and his fellow
Marines.
</P>
<P>
   ''It didn't matter,'' Francesco Leto said of the apology. ''My
son is no longer here.''
</P>
<P>
   Under military law, Arana could have been confined for nine
months. While accepting the outcome, Domenica Leto said life will
never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a pair of his shoes still by our back door,'' his
mother said. ''I can't move those shoes. I just can't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
