<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workers Strike Texas Lockheed Plant  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN HAWKINS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Machinists walked picket lines today at
Lockheed Martin Aeronautics Co.'s huge aircraft plant after voting
to strike over better wages and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The plant is Lockheed's primary manufacturer of the F-16
fighter, said company spokesman Joe Stout.
</P>
<P>
   Angry that their wages and bonuses from the defense contractor
have fallen behind rival Boeing Co. machinists, members of Local
776 of the International Association of Machinists voted 1,392 to
275 on Sunday to go on strike. Their three-year contract expired at
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear what effect the strike would have
on company operations, Stout said today. He would not say how many
workers honored the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people on strike are morning-shift employees who
work on the F-16.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed stock was down 6\ cents at $21 a share this afternoon
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its work on the F-16, the Fort Worth operation is
the only Lockheed plant that produces part of the fuselage for the
F-22 fighter and parts for the Japanese F-2 fighter, according to
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed has made several major sales during the past two years,
most notably 80 planes to the United Arab Emirates, 50 each to
Israel and Greece, and 24 to Egypt. It is a finalist for several
other contracts, including sales to Norway and Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed is Tarrant County's second-largest employer with a work
force of about 10,500.
</P>
<P>
   No new talks were scheduled after the walkout, only the third in
the plant's 59 years of operation. A walkout in 1984 lasted for two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Contract talks began in mid-February and continued through last
week. Stout said management made its last offer on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Health care benefits were a major issue. In February, Local 776
President Pat Lane said Lockheed was asking workers to pay higher
premiums for fewer benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The union represents some of the plant's most senior employees.
Because of defense downsizing and seniority rules, the average
worker at the plant is 49 years old and has 20 years of seniority.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.lockheedmartin.com
</P>
<P>
   The union: http://www.iamaw.org
</P>
</TEXT>
