<HEADLINE> State indefinitely suspends dentist's license  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A state board on Monday indefinitely
suspended the license of dentist Kevin Ward while he fights charges
he left five children with broken bones and bruises while holding
them down to work on their teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Ward and the state attorney general's office agreed
to let Ward work weekday afternoons on paperwork at his Union City
office but barred him from any contact with patients until his case
is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office asked the state Board of Dentistry
to keep Ward from treating children after families came forward to
say Ward broke the leg of a 5-year-old boy, the thumb of a
10-year-old girl and the wrist of a 4-year-old girl over the past
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Ward also left a 6-year-old and a 3-year-old with bumps and
bruises after holding the children down forcefully in 1999, state
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the board referred the charges at Ward's request to
the Office of Administrative Law, which will schedule hearings on
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Ward filed court papers Monday denying charges he had covered
the mouths and noses of patients and pushed down on patients'
chests with his fist to restrain them.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has restrained unruly, uncooperative children, but
followed guidelines set by the American Academy of Pediatric
Dentistry.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines state that ''partial or complete immobilization
of the patient sometimes is necessary'' but says that a doctor has
to obtain a parent's consent before doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Ward's patients have said that he never allowed parents in the
treatment room.
</P>
<P>
   Ward has treated more than 50,000 children, mostly Medicaid
patients, in the past seven years, and most have had no complaints,
said Ward's attorney, John Dizzia.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dr. Ward has devoted his practice to caring for children,''
Dizzia said Monday. ''This is a handful of cases'' before the
board, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He is being sued by the parents of 5-year-old Mario Rivero, who
is in a chest-high cast and does not expect to walk for months
after his leg was broken in Ward's office on Feb. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Rivero's father, Mario, said that Ward told him he pressed down
on Rivero's leg after the child kicked him, then continued working
on his teeth after he heard the bone snap.
</P>
<P>
   Ward suggested to the boy's mother, Yeni Rivero, that the boy
see a doctor after depositing him in a chair in the waiting room,
Mario Rivero said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This man had no sympathy; he had no expression. This man
didn't have any worries at all,'' Mario Rivero said.
</P>
<P>
   He also faces a lawsuit by the mother of Amanda Schwab, who
broke her wrist in Ward's office when the then 4-year-old came into
get a tooth pulled in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ward has not been criminally charged with any of the incidents,
nor with the 1984 death of a 4-year-old boy who overdosed on
anesthesia under his care. The board suspended his license for a
year in 1987 but stayed it, meaning he was never barred from
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ''This time he's not going to get away,'' Mario Rivero said
Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
