<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Audra McDonald  </HEADLINE>
By SAMANTHA CRITCHELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- She is a talented soprano whose name graces
marquees across the country, filling theaters with audiences eager
to hear her versions of old-time standards and new cutting-edge
compositions.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean Audra McDonald is a diva.
</P>
<P>
   ''People think all singers are divas and that is definitely not
the case with me. I am so normal and boring,'' said McDonald.
''Your girl-next-door -- that's me.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-time Tony Award winner packs and unpacks her own
suitcases, graciously thanks passers-by for their compliments, and
even picks up after her German shepherd-Rottweiler.
</P>
<P>
   But don't offer her any cheese.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview at a Manhattan coffee shop, McDonald orders
a chicken salad without its accompanying cheese and double-checks
with the waitress to make sure the dressing is cheese-free.
</P>
<P>
   ''I used to do cheese a lot, but it started to affect my voice,
so I stopped,'' McDonald explained. ''It's like chocolate, and I'll
cheat, but I can't do it when I'm working.''
</P>
<P>
   She also avoids talking on the phone and drinking alcohol when
she is preparing for shows and concerts. But doing Pilates and yoga
is good for her body, soul and voice, she said.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald, 29, graduated from The Juilliard School for the
performing arts in 1993. She has built a resume of high-profile
Broadway roles, including ''Ragtime,'' ''Carousel'' and ''Marie
Christine.''
</P>
<P>
   She will perform in Atlanta, Boston and Washington, D.C., on the
second leg of her spring concert tour (April 25-May 14). She will
also appear in ''Sweeney Todd'' with the New York Philharmonic (May
1-7).
</P>
<P>
   In a complete change of pace, McDonald has the role of a
criminal psychologist in two upcoming episodes of NBC's ''Law and
Order: Special Victims Unit.''
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic, non-singing role is ''a chance for me to stretch
and flex other muscles,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald appeared in ABC's ''Annie'' and in the CBS movie
''Having Our Say: The Delany Sisters' First 100 Years.'' Both
programs were honored with Peabody awards for broadcast or cable
excellence this year.
</P>
<P>
   Her second solo CD, ''How Glory Goes'' (Nonesuch Records), was
released in February.
</P>
<P>
   1. Since you have an affinity with old-fashioned musicals, do
you think you were born a few decades too late?
</P>
<P>
   McDonald: Musicals were as popular, if not more popular, in the
1940s as action movies are now. Judy Garland was also in the Top 40
in the '40s. No such thing now, so in some ways, I think I was born
late. But sometimes I think that because of my color, I wouldn't
have the opportunities that I have now if I were born in the '40s,
so in some ways it's a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   2. Is there a role you'd really like to tackle?
</P>
<P>
   McDonald: There are certain revivals I would like to do. I'm
sort of on this kick that I'd like to do Eliza from 'My Fair Lady,'
and once I'm ready, I'd like to do Shakespeare. But I'd really,
really have to study up for that. And Bess of 'Porgy and Bess.'
</P>
<P>
   3. Do you have a dream place where you would really like to
perform?
</P>
<P>
   McDonald: (laughing) I want to do a concert in Bali. My music
director and I were joking that we need to get the Honolulu Opera
to sponsor our next concert. And Australia ... I'm really curious
about Australia.
</P>
<P>
   4. Do you think musical talent is inherited?
</P>
<P>
   McDonald: I think that anyone can develop a musical talent. You
can learn to play the piano. ... I think with singing, it helps to
be born with some ability to sing, but any talent can be developed
or nurtured.
</P>
<P>
   5. When did you know that you had that natural ability?
</P>
<P>
   McDonald: I would sing really loud when I was a kid in church.
My parents figured out then that I could sing.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Audra McDonald fan site: http://www.audra-mcdonald.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-10-00 1359 </TRAILER>
