<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 162.50; Dow Up 110.76  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed today, with blue-chip
shares pulling the Dow Jones industrials higher and technology
shares slumping as investors wondered whether upcoming
first-quarter earnings reports will justify the high prices of tech
issues.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow was up 110.76 at
11,222.24. Financial shares led the advance after a Merrill Lynch
strategist recommended clients move some money from technology
stocks into financials. American Express rose 3 11/16 to 142} and
J.P. Morgan rose 4 3/16 to 134 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were lower. The Nasdaq composite index
was down 162.50 at 4,283.95, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was down 2.75 to 1,513.60.
</P>
<P>
   Technology shares, still vulnerable after last week's wild
gyrations, were mixed. Microsoft fell 2} to 86 5/16, and Applied
Materials lost 4] to 110{ on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Yahoo! lost 5 23/64 to 145 49/64 and BroadVision fell 8
11/16 to 47].
</P>
<P>
   Investors are waiting to see whether earnings reports for the
recently ended first quarter will show the rapid growth that
convinced many people to bid technology stocks to unprecedented
levels earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Chip maker Motorola was scheduled to report earnings today, with
Advanced Micro Devices and Rambus to follow on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Those stocks were mixed today. Advanced Micro Devices led the
group, rising } to 74~.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, ''first-quarter earnings should be good and include
some positive surprises,'' said Gail Dudack, chief investment
strategist at Warburg Dillon Read in New York. She said the biggest
surprises -- companies that easily exceed analysts' published
forecasts -- should come from the old-line energy and utility
industries.
</P>
<P>
   A similar vote of confidence came from Richard McCabe, chief
market analyst at Merrill Lynch. McCabe told clients today they
should reduce their exposure to technology stocks in favor of
energy, financial and consumer issues.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont rose 3| to 58| and 3M rose 1 11/16 to 93 5/16, helping
pull the Dow higher.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris fell 1 7/16 to 21{. On Friday, a Florida jury
ruled that the company, along with other large cigarette makers,
must pay $6.9 million in compensatory damages to sick smokers.
Philip Morris has vowed to fight any punitive damages in the next
phase of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a slender margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 571.16 million
shares, well behind Friday's pace. On the Nasdaq, decliners led by
a 2-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies plunged 13.63 to
529.36.
</P>
