<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family accuses Bronx cops of executing son  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Bronx district attorney's office has
withheld evidence that police shot an unarmed man in the head at
point-blank range while he lay face down and helpless in a
stairwell, the victim's family claimed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''They executed him,'' Juanita Young, mother of Malcolm
Ferguson, said at a news conference. ''Only they know the reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson, 23 -- labeled a ''serious criminal'' by Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani -- was killed March 1 during a confrontation with narcotics
officers in a Bronx apartment building. His family demanded
District Attorney Robert Johnson make public the results of an
investigation it said will back allegations he was murdered.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm disappointed at the D.A.'s office for stonewalling here,''
said James Ferguson, the victim's father. ''I'm also disappointed
at the character assassination of my son.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Johnson, Steven Reed, said the investigation is
ongoing. He refused further comment.
</P>
<P>
   The family -- which is planning a wrongful death lawsuit against
the city -- contended that a private forensics expert and
prosecutors had reached the same conclusion: that Ferguson was
killed by a shot fired from a gun pressed to his head. Citing the
controversial police slayings of Patrick Dorismond in March and
Amadou Diallo in February 1999, family attorney Andrew Miller also
charged the killing fits a deadly pattern of abuse against
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   In the Ferguson case, police ''were acting on the suspicion that
if several black men are congregating together, something bad must
be going on,'' he said. ''Clearly, these intrusive searches
targeting young black men must come to an end before another
tragedy occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Police say Ferguson, a parolee who was carrying heroin, was
killed after he and other drug suspects were stopped by members of
a plainclothes narcotics unit. When he broke away and tried to
flee, Officer Louis Rivera caught him in the stairwell; a struggle
ensued and the officer's 9 mm Smith &AMP; Wesson discharged once,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Defending the shooting, authorities noted Ferguson was a
convicted drug dealer with at least nine prior arrests on his
record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-10-00 1430 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
