<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Monday, April 10, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fed Tries To Modernize Check System
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
today the central bank is trying to modernize its check-processing
system and is testing new electronic systems. He also noted,
however, that even in this Internet age, many people still cling to
paper checks for privacy considerations and also because of ''a
deep psychological connection between money and tangible wealth.''
Americans write some 68 billion checks a year, and Greenspan said
the number is expected to increase. He remarks were transmitted by
satellite to a meeting in Los Angeles of the National Automated
Clearinghouse Association, a financial industry consortium. He said
'' ... whatever innovations develop, the check will likely be with
us for many years.''
</P>
<P>
   World Bank Protesters Arrested
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Protesters were out today in advance of the
coming weekend meeting of world finance ministers. A group of about
20 demonstrated and briefly blocked a street near the World Bank
headquarters. Police said seven were arrested. Some chained
themselves to a rental truck that had a banner saying ''World Bank
plunders the planet'' and objecting to financing of oil, gas and
mining activities.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Down 167.35; Dow Up 127.82
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed today, with blue-chip
shares pushing the Dow Jones industrials higher and technology
shares slumping as investors wondered whether upcoming
first-quarter earnings reports will justify the high prices of tech
issues. Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow was up 127.82 at 11,239.30.
Financial shares led the advance after a Merrill Lynch strategist
recommended clients move some money from technology stocks into
financials. American Express rose 3 11/16 to 142} and J.P. Morgan
rose 4 3/16 to 134 1/16. Broader stock indicators were lower. The
Nasdaq composite index was down 167.35 at 4,279.10.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 3 p.m. EDT:
Dow Industrials:        11239.30 + 127.82
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1486  Declines 1415  Unchgd  505
NYSE Volume:         619,102,320
Most Active NYSE issue:         Compaq Computer 30       +   \  
S&AMP;P 500:         1513.53  - 2.82
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          965.23 -  23.46
Nasdaq Composite Index        4279.10 - 167.35
Gold(final) -    $282.00    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.
</P>
<P>
   Workers Strike Texas Lockheed Plant
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Machinists walked picket lines today at
Lockheed Martin Aeronautics Co.'s huge aircraft plant after voting
to strike for better wages and benefits. The plant is Lockheed's
primary manufacturer of the F-16 fighter, said company spokesman
Joe Stout. Angry that their wages and bonuses from the defense
contractor have fallen behind rival Boeing Co. machinists, members
of Local 776 of the International Association of Machinists voted
1,392 to 275 on Sunday to go on strike. Their three-year contract
expired at midnight. It was not immediately clear what effect the
strike would have on company operations, Stout said today. He would
not say how many workers honored the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds and Reynolds To Shed Unit
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- The Reynolds and Reynolds Co. said today it
plans to sell or spin off its document services business within six
months to concentrate on its automotive division. The document
services unit, called the Information Services Group, makes
business forms for hospitals and other businesses. It accounted for
$730 million of the company's $1.56 billion in revenues for fiscal
1999. The automotive division of the Dayton-based company helps car
dealers and manufacturers manage their computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Bumpy Road Slows Digital TV Rollout
</P>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS (AP) -- The road to digital TV is filled with potholes
and little agreement on who is responsible for fixing them. TV
makers say broadcasters must create more content in the super-sharp
format, known as high-definition, to spur consumers to buy digital
sets. Broadcasters, meeting here this week for their annual
convention, say manufacturers must develop better digital TVs and
make them compatible with cable boxes. And both industries fear
that talk by some about changing digital standards could cause the
whole project to unravel. ''This is an evolution. It's not going to
happen overnight ...,'' warned Dick Wiley, a former Federal
Communications Commission chairman who headed a nine-year
government panel on digital TV.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett Earnings Rise 19 Percent
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Strong advertising revenues from USA Today
and other newspapers boosted Gannett Co.'s earnings by 19 percent
in the first quarter, the company reported Monday. Gannett earned
$203 million, excluding a one-time gain from the sale of a cable
division, in the quarter ended March 26, compared to $170 million
for the same period a year earlier. The company earned 74 cents per
share in the quarter, compared to 61 cents per share for the same
period in 1999. Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial
had projected earnings of 73 cents per share. Revenues increased 15
percent to $1.36 billion, from $1.18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Heavy, Boeing May Team
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Mitsubishi Heavy Industries is in talks with Boeing
Co. about a possible tie-up in the aerospace industry, a spokesman
for the Japanese manufacturer said today. He commented after two
newspapers reported over the weekend that the two companies had
agreed on a comprehensive alliance in the aerospace business and
Boeing later denied the report. Today, the Mitsubishi spokesman
declined to give details of the Mitsubishi-Boeing talks.
</P>
<P>
   Honda To Build CR-Vs in Britain
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The British car industry, still reeling from BMW's
plan to sell off the Rover Group, got a welcome boost today when
Japan's Honda announced plans to build a new four-wheel-drive
vehicle at its plant in England. Honda Motor Co. Ltd. said it will
start producing its CR-V model in June at its factory in Swindon,
Wiltshire, to help meet strong demand in Europe. Although Honda
will not be hiring additional workers to make the CR-V, the
announcement was perceived as a vote of confidence in the British
carmaking industry. The government has suffered intense criticism
over its handling of BMW's sale of Rover.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan To Sell Aerospace Unit
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese carmaker Nissan Motor Co. said today that
it will sell its aerospace division to cut debt and focus on its
ailing automotive business. The affiliate of France's Renault SA
will sell its aerospace business to Japanese heavy-equipment maker
Ishikawajima-Harima Heavy Industries on July 1, pending approval by
its shareholders and government regulatory officials, the company
said. Nissan did not disclose terms of the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda Joins Test for Fuel Cell Cars
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Mazda Motor Corp. said today it will join the
Japanese unit of DaimlerChrysler AG and a Japanese oil company in a
government-led project to test fuels for next-generation vehicles.
Japan's Trade Ministry will contribute about two-thirds of the
$3.77 million to $4.71 million it will cost to test
fuel-cell-powered vehicles, said Keiichi Yumoto, an official in the
ministry's Natural Resources and Energy Agency. Yumoto said the aim
of the three-year project is to help decide which fuels are most
appropriate for use in Japan. fuels to be tested include methanol
and hydrogen, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: Jobless claims
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: Producer prices
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: Retail sales
</P>
<P>
   Friday: Consumer prices
</P>
<P>
   Friday: Business inventories
</P>
<P>
   Friday: Industrial production
</P>
</TEXT>
