<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rates Fall at Treasury Bill Auction  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities fell in Monday's auction.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department sold $8.5 billion in three-month bills
at a discount rate of 5.680 percent, down from 5.710 percent last
week. An additional $7.5 billion was sold in six-month bills at a
rate of 5.855 percent, down from 5.900 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The three-month rate was the lowest since Feb. 28 when the bills
sold for 5.670 percent. The six-month rate was the lowest since
March 6 when the rate was 5.825.
</P>
<P>
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
-- 5.844 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,856.40 and 6.117 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,704.00
</P>
<P>
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 6.17
percent last week from 6.30 percent the previous week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-10-00 1537 </TRAILER>
