<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Falls More Than 200  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology shares slumped Monday, dragging down
the Nasdaq composite index as investors wondered whether
first-quarter earnings reports will justify their high prices. The
Dow industrials gained ground.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-focused Nasdaq, which remains vulnerable after
last week's steep swings, was down 211.79, or 4.8 percent, at
4,234.66 at late afternoon. The Dow Jones industrial average was up
68.56 at 11,180.04.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are waiting to see whether earnings reports for the
recently ended first quarter will show the rapid growth that
persuaded many people to bid technology stocks to unprecedented
levels earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, ''first-quarter earnings should be good and include
some positive surprises,'' said Gail Dudack, chief investment
strategist at Warburg Dillon Read in New York. She said the biggest
surprises -- companies that easily exceed analysts' published
forecasts -- should come from the old-line energy and utility
industries.
</P>
<P>
   Richard McCabe, chief market analyst at Merrill Lynch, offered
similar advice to clients. He recommended that they reduce their
exposure to technology stocks in favor of energy, financial and
consumer issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-10-00 1541 </TRAILER>
