<DOCNO> APW20000410.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Tries To Modernize Check System  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan, recognizing that
many Americans still cling to paper checks in the electronic age,
said Monday that the Federal Reserve is moving to modernize its
check processing system and is testing new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan noted in a speech to an industry group that, even in
the age of the Internet, many people still prefer paper checks
because of privacy concerns and ''a deep psychological connection
between money and tangible wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans write some 68 billion checks a year, and Greenspan
said the number is expected to increase. At the same time, industry
experiments are taking place with technologies such as electronic
money that don't require bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ''The average consumer is exceptionally conservative and
traditional when it comes to money, which has a profoundly
important role in day-to-day living,'' Greenspan said in his
address transmitted by satellite to a meeting in Los Angeles of the
National Automated Clearinghouse Association, a financial industry
consortium.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tampering with money has always had profoundly political
implications,'' Greenspan told the group. ''It took many
generations for people to feel comfortable accepting paper in lieu
of gold or silver. It is taking almost as long to convince them
that holding money and making payments in ephemeral electronic form
is as secure as using paper.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Greenspan said, there is the paradox of the
nation's systems for handling big payments, banking records and
securities transactions being electronic while consumer payments
still are made by currency and checks.
</P>
<P>
   ''As we look forward, the Federal Reserve recognizes that
whatever innovations develop, the check will likely be with us for
many years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the central bank is testing new systems for electronic
presenting of checks, which include capturing and storing
electronic images of checks and allowing banks to make payment
decisions in real time by getting access to the images over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A voluntary pilot project in Montana, started last spring,
allows banks to use electronic pictures of checks so they don't
have to be physically carted from one location to another -- an
effort that could bring faster check clearing and fraud detection.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed also is working to improve the efficiency of its check
clearing services, Greenspan said. The central bank, which has 43
check-processing offices across the country, also began a
nationwide computer modernization project last year.
</P>
<P>
   He said it would be a mistake for the government to step in and
impose standards or regulations for electronic payments on the
banking industry, since ''only consumers and merchants will
ultimately determine what new products are successful in the
marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hall, a spokesman for the American Bankers Association,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Government intervention ''could really put a damper on new
technologies and innovations,'' he said. ''Consumers are ultimately
going to drive this.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Text of Greenspan's speech:
http://www.federalreserve.gov/boarddocs/speeches/2000/20000410.htm
</P>
<P>
   National Automated Clearinghouse Association's Web site:
http://www.nacha.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
