<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks End Mixed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- A late erosion of technology and telecom gains
left European stocks mixed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks companies in
countries that joined the single currency, was up 0.53 points at
5,282.3 at 1600 GMT. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index was up 22.7
points at 5,282.3.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies fell
4.3 points, or 0.1 percent, to 392.89, while the Dow Jones Stoxx 50
Index fell 4.3 points, or 0.1 percent, to 5,042.5.
</P>
<P>
   The poor opening of the Nasdaq market in New York pulled down
gains in technology and telecom stocks. With a European Central
Bank interest rate decision and key U.S. data due later this week,
many analysts believe European investors are being cautious.
</P>
<P>
   London's FTSE-100 Share Index fell 36.5 points to 6,533.4. After
Nasdaq's early fall, technology stocks joined wide-based old
economy losses to drag the index down.
</P>
<P>
   Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index fell 5.25 points to 7,516 as
technology and telecom gains diminished in late trading. Deutsche
Telekom rose after reports that the flotation of its internet arm,
T-Online, was already oversubscribed. BMW also rose, after denying
weekend press claims the Quandt family, the main shareholder, was
on the verge of selling its stake.
</P>
<P>
   The Paris CAC-40 Index rose 56.86 points, or 0.9 percent, to
6,364.9. Its earlier tech and telecom gains were diluted after
Nasdaq's opening.
</P>
<P>
   Milan's MIBtel Index finished 30 points down at 31405 after a
strong tech-based open as traders worried over Nasdaq's fall.
</P>
<P>
   Amsterdam's AEX Index closed up 0.69 points, or 0.1 percent at
672.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
