<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cornell volunteers spend month sampling extraterrestrial cuisine  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) --It took an out-of-this-world menu to make
Elizabeth Babcock Woodring pass up a taste of her wedding cake.
</P>
<P>
   Woodring was among 16 volunteers at Cornell University who dined
exclusively on space food for 30 days as part of NASA-funded
project to develop extraterrestrial cuisine for future astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hardest part was not being able to eat what we wanted when
we wanted, like late at night,'' said Woodring, a laboratory
technician in plant science at Cornell who got married during the
study and had to freeze a piece of her wedding cake to eat later.
</P>
<P>
   ''In general, the food was delicious, and I'm trying to make my
diet more like theirs,'' Woodring said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists were under many constraints as they tried to develop
a diet for space travelers.
</P>
<P>
   The space food diet consisted primarily of vegan foods, no meat
or dairy products. The dishes, all previously tested in weekly
taste panels, were plant-based foods that had to be tasty,
nutritious and economical, said Jean Hunter, an associate professor
of agricultural and biological engineering who is heading the
project.
</P>
<P>
   The food also had to be low in salt -- because sodium from
recycled urine in a space colony would be bad for crops. Low in
iron -- for space adaptation. Not labor intensive -- astronauts' time
is at a premium. And sparing in their use of any ingredients
difficult to produce in a space colony.
</P>
<P>
   The menu also had to be derived from a very limited list of
crops, mainly wheat, rice, soybeans and other vegetables that can
be grown hydroponically in artificially lighted,
temperature-controlled space farms, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fare for a typical day might include sweet potato pancakes and
scrambled tofu for breakfast, lentil loaf sandwiches or seitan
tacos for lunch, and carrot drumsticks and tabouli salad for dinner
with chocolate soy candy for dessert.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to find out if our space foods wear well and
maintain their appeal if consumed as a complete diet for 30 days,''
Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, researchers analyzed acceptability ratings from the
participants and food consumption. Additionally, researchers
studied the physical and psychological side effects of the
low-salt, high-fiber diet by tracking body weight and daily
measures of health, well-being and mood, Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Participants lost between 3 and 7 pounds on the monthlong diet,
probably because of its low sodium content, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Findings from the space-food diet study not only will help NASA
plan on how best to feed an extended space mission team but could
better inform the health care industry, said David Levitsky, a
nutritional sciences professor at Cornell who is collaborating in
the study.
</P>
<P>
   So far, researchers have developed about 250 recipes ready for
space, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-10-00 1606 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000410.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans Grain Down on Crop Outlook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures slumped Monday on the
Chicago Board of Trade amid a spate of wet weather and generally
improved conditions for crops.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat prices fell more than 2 percent as a combination of
factors led to a big selloff. A weekend cold snap didn't produce
the crop damage that some had feared, soil moisture is steadily
improving, and investors were jockeying for position ahead of the
weekly supply-and-demand report due out Tuesday by the U.S.
Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the decline was considered technically driven.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans tumbled after weekend showers in the Midwest provided
much-needed soil moisture for the eastern soybean belt. Additional
pressure came from forecasts for more showers Tuesday and again
later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Corn prices also were lower because of the weekend rains.
</P>
<P>
   Recent precipitation has dissipated some of the concern that the
nation's leading crops could be badly hurt by the dry conditions
that have been prevalent in much of the Midwest since last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery fell 6 cents to $2.65 a bushel; May corn
fell 2\ cents to $2.27 a bushel; July oats were unchanged at $1.19}
a bushel; May soybeans fell 6} cents to $5.32 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef futures were higher on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
while pork futures were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle rose .02 cent to 69.12 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle rose .50 cent to 84.50 cents a pound; June lean hogs
rose .40 cent to 74.40 cents a pound; May pork bellies fell the
limit 3 cents to 93.42 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-10-00 1621 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000410.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Ends Off 258; Dow Up 106  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology shares slumped today, pulling the
Nasdaq composite index down more than 250 points and proving that
the nervousness and volatility that shook Wall Street last week has
not left the market. Blue-chip stocks rose, however, as investors
sought their more stable and predictable returns.
</P>
<P>
   According to preliminary calculations, the Nasdaq composite
index was down 258.27 at 4,188.18, its second largest point drop
ever. The increasingly volatile index has recorded nine of its 10
worst point drops since the start of the year, as well as nine of
its 10 biggest point gains.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 106.73 at 11,186.56.
Financial shares led the advance after a Merrill Lynch strategist
recommended clients move some money from technology stocks into
financials.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mostly lower.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 11.89 to 1,504.46.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-6 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 1,618 down, 1,386 up and 464
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 850.18 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.
888.41 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 19.25 to
523.74.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks fell in a steady spiral as investors wondered
whether upcoming first-quarter earnings reports will justify the
high prices of tech issues. The selloff was a clear indication that
the weakness that gripped the sector last week has not run its
course, said Tony Dwyer, chief market strategist at Kirlin
Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rebound we saw last Friday was just too quick,'' he said.
''The market is not back to normal, because valuations for a lot of
these technology stocks remain too extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   Declines hit a broad array of technology stocks. Microsoft and
Applied Materials fell steeply on the Nasdaq. Yahoo! and
BroadVision also declined.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Dwyer said, many investors hopped back into the
market on the promise of strong first-quarter earnings. The
reporting season picks up this week, with several prominent
technology companies -- Motorola, Advanced Micro Devices and Rambus
-- among the first to report.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those stocks turned lower today after early gains.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fundamentals are terrific,'' Dwyer said. ''You can't
debate that. But a lot of that strength is priced into the stock
price already.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, many Wall Street strategists have reminded
clients that the strongest earnings growth this quarter is expected
not from the technology sector, but from the less heralded energy
sector. Oil companies are expected to reap the benefits of a spike
in crude oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Today, widespread circulation of a research note from Richard
McCabe, chief market analyst at Merrill Lynch, helped draw some
investors away from technology and into Old Economy stocks. McCabe
told clients they should reduce their exposure to technology stocks
in favor of energy, financial and consumer issues.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont and 3M rose, helping pull the Dow higher.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris fell after a Florida jury said Friday that the
company, along with other large cigarette makers, must pay $6.9
million in compensatory damages to sick smokers. Philip Morris has
vowed to fight any punitive damages in the next phase of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-10-00 1632 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000410.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
