<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Seeks E. German Secret Files  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Former Chancellor Helmut Kohl has asked to see the
files the East German spy agency kept on him, the office keeping
the archive said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The files compiled by the Stasi on Kohl and other Christian
Democratic officials have become the latest twist in the party's
financing scandal, with Kohl demanding that his files not be made
public.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal plaguing Kohl's Christian Democrats exploded after
he admitted accepting up to $1 million in donations from sources he
has refused to name. Some have speculated that the answer may be in
the files kept by the communist Stasi.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's lawyers have given the agency in charge of the files an
April 14 deadline to declare whether they will make the files
available, and if so, have threatened to take legal measures to
stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the agency keeping the files, however, has said the
law allows for publication of files kept on historical figures --
except for information relating to intimate life or health.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Monday report in the Tagesspiegel newspaper, the
Stasi files on Kohl stretch back to 1975 when he was governor of
Rhineland-Palatinate state. Later the Stasi even monitored
telephone calls from his official residence, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   From the time Kohl became chancellor in 1982, the Stasi compiled
up to 30 pages of files a week, the newspaper said. Some 30 of
Kohl's closest aides were also spied upon, including his office
manager Juliane Weber, with the Stasi concentrating on facts of an
internal and compromising nature.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman from the agency keeping the files said research of
the contents of Stasi telephone eavesdropping records was
incomplete, and that the files themselves were piecemeal.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament investigators have said they can't use the files as
evidence because they were illegally obtained. However, some have
said they could be used to spark questions to witnesses. Kohl is
scheduled to testify in late June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
