<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Viacom Chief Seeks To Seal Deal  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Viacom hopes to complete its merger with CBS
this month without having to shed the UPN network and will continue
to push for greater relaxation of other limits on media ownership,
the company's chief said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The broadcast industry is very, very big,'' Viacom Chairman
Sumner Redstone said. ''It's an enormous business. We have
tremendous competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal awaits approval by the Justice Department and the
Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   One of the wrinkles the companies have been trying to iron out
is an FCC rule that forbids a company from owning two or more
networks in certain combinations. The combination of CBS and Viacom
-- which owns UPN -- would run afoul of that restriction.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is currently evaluating the dual network ban and
other media ownership regulations as part of a mandated review.
Alternately, the companies could get a waiver to keep UPN.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone said that keeping the fledgling network in the
Viacom-CBS fold is key for its survival.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no public service argument that could be made that
would warrant the death of UPN, which is just what would happen if
we don't get it,'' Redstone said. He said he hopes and expects they
will be able to keep UPN. ''If we keep it, it will succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Another regulation that prohibits one company from owning
stations that reach more than 35 percent of U.S. households is
outdated and doesn't reflect the changes in the industry, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue to fight very hard for relief from the caps
because they just don't make any sense in the world in which we
live today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone thinks there is support in Washington for easing the
cap, but said he doesn't anticipate the rule will be changed before
Viacom closes its deal with CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC also is looking at whether to modify or keep as is the
national ownership cap as part of its media review.
</P>
<P>
   In a keynote address to the industry group, Redstone reassured
broadcasters that they have the most valuable assets -- content and
brand name -- to enable them to succeed in a period of rapid change
in the media market.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a new media world, the advantage belongs to broadcasters,''
Redstone told the group. ''When it comes to technology, the
opportunities far exceed the threat ... because the content is and
will remain the driving force.''
</P>
<P>
   That same theme was echoed by NAB president Edward Fritts, who
told his membership that broadcasters' ties to the community and
audience share give them a huge strategic advantage.
</P>
<P>
   While high-tech companies have investors with money, ''they
don't have the eyes and ears that broadcasters can deliver,'' said
Fritts. ''What broadcasters must realize is that we what we deliver
is ever more important than how we deliver it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
