<HEADLINE> EU Toughens Myanmar Sanctions  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUXEMBOURG (AP) -- European Union foreign ministers on Monday
toughened sanctions against Myanmar, saying the country's military
government has intensified repression of civil and political
rights.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the EU banned visits by Myanmar officials, withdrew
trade privileges and imposed an arms embargo on the nation, also
known as Burma.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers on Monday added a ban on equipment ''that
might be used for repression'' and agreed to freeze funds held
abroad by members of Myanmar's military regime.
</P>
<P>
   The visa ban on traveling officials also was toughened by
listing specifically those members in Myanmar's military regime to
whom it applied, the ministers said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But the ministers ''reaffirmed the importance'' for good
relations with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations -- a
regional grouping that includes Myanmar -- and proposed a
ministerial meeting with ASEAN nations later this year.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, high-level EU-ASEAN meetings have been
canceled because the ASEAN side refused to drop Myanmar from its
ranks to please the Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   In their statement, the EU ministers deplored ''the continuing
and intensified repression of civil and political rights (in
Myanmar) as well as the harsh conditions hindering the people's
enjoyment of economic, social and cultural rights.''
</P>
<P>
   They again urged Myanmar s leaders ''to respect human rights,
restore democracy and engage in a dialogue with the opposition that
could lead to national reconciliation in a united and democratic
state.''
</P>
<P>
   The EU reviews its sanctions against Myanmar every six months.
The measures are designed to punish Myanmar military leaders for
not turning over power to a democratically elected government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
