<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't: Traffickers Behind Protests  </HEADLINE>
By PETER McFARREN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) -- The government accused cocaine
traffickers Monday of organizing weeklong demonstrations in Bolivia
by farmers and workers protesting rising prices and unemployment in
South America's poorest country.
</P>
<P>
   The protests, which have virtually shut down Cochabamba,
Bolivia's third largest city, continued Monday despite a security
crackdown that has left six dead and a ''state of siege'' decree
giving police a freer rein.
</P>
<P>
   Information Minister Ronald MacLean claimed the demonstrations
were led by drug traffickers trying to stop a government program to
eradicate production of coca leaf, used to make cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ''These protests are a conspiracy financed by cocaine
trafficking looking for pretexts to carry out subversive
activities,'' MacLean said. ''It is impossible for so many farmers
to spontaneously move on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   MacLean said President Hugo Banzer is worried because
''political groups and traffickers are instigating farmers to
confront the army.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the organizers of the protests is Evo Morales, leader of
the country's coca leaf producers, who strongly oppose the
government's campaign to replace coca leaf crops with others, such
as cotton and bananas.
</P>
<P>
   The destruction of coca leaf production has deprived thousands
of peasants of their sole income.
</P>
<P>
   The marches began April 3 in Cochabamba, a city of 500,000
located 350 miles east of La Paz. It has since been paralyzed and
isolated by road blocks, marches and clashes.
</P>
<P>
   The Cochabamba protests were prompted by a 20 percent increase
in city water rates, and demonstrations quickly spread to other
cities with thousands protesting unemployment and economic
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   A ''state of siege'' decree passed Saturday suspended many
constitutional guarantees, allowing police to detain protest
leaders without a warrant, restricting travel and political
activity and establishing a curfew.
</P>
<P>
   Six people have been killed and scores wounded in clashes around
the country as the government sent thousands of army soldiers into
city streets and urban roads to try put down the protests.
</P>
<P>
   Still, thousands of farmers and city dwellers continued marches
and rallies Monday. Protesters manned roadblocks near the Andean
towns of Achacachi and Batallas, where one army officer and two
farmers were killed and dozens injured on Sunday. The army cleared
the block in other areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are protesting because of higher gasoline and
transportation prices and a law that will charge us for the use of
water,'' said Felix Santos, a farmers' leader.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers at rural public schools went on strike Monday demanding
salary increases and the end of the state of siege. Students fought
running skirmishes with police in La Paz.
</P>
<P>
   The destruction of more than half of the country's coca leaf
production has left thousands of Quechua and Aymara Indian farmers
without a livelihood and depressed the economy in regions including
Cochabamba, where cocaine trafficking once thrived.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
