<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spirit Airlines defends safety record after back-to-back incidents  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMONA, N.J. (AP) -- The head of safety for Spirit Airlines
defended the company Monday following back-to-back incidents in
which jets were forced to return to Atlantic City International
Airport after takeoff because of mechanical problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're disturbed, as we always are when we have any kind of
problem. However, the crews handled them both very professionally.
We're happy with that. Nobody was hurt,'' said Robert Moreland,
vice president of safety for the Fort Lauderdale, Fla.,-based
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   He said no passenger has ever been injured on a Spirit flight.
The discount carrier, which flies to resorts in South Carolina and
Florida, began flying in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Flight 303 to Orlando turned around within 20 minutes
of its departure when passengers and crew reported smelling smoke.
The DC-9 aircraft, with 109 people aboard, landed safely and no
fire was detected. Four hours later, the passengers boarded another
Spirit plane and made the flight to Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   A bearing problem in the plane's air-recycling unit caused the
unit to overheat, emitting the burning smell, according to Moreland
and Federal Aviation Administration spokeswoman Arlene Salac.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Flight 541 to Myrtle Beach, S.C., suffered the
failure of its primary engine as it lifted off from Atlantic City
International.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers reported hearing an explosion. ''At first, I assumed
it was the landing gear lifting up,'' Jeff West, 36, of Edgewater
Park, told The Press of Atlantic City. ''But then I knew that
wasn't it. I turned to my buddy and said, 'That's a noise I never
heard before.''
</P>
<P>
   The plane, with 148 people aboard, returned to the airport on
the strength of the second engine within 20 minutes and landed
without incident. But the engine problem apparently sparked a brush
fire near the runway as it took off. It was extinguished, said
Peter Hartt, a spokesman for the South Jersey Transportation
Authority, which operates the airport.
</P>
<P>
   In that incident, a turbine lost one or more blades, knocking it
out of balance and forcing the pilot to shut it down, Moreland
said.
</P>
<P>
   Salac said the FAA would look into the second incident to
determine whether there was some ''systemic'' problem with thet
Pratt Whitney JT8D-217 engine.
</P>
<P>
   But she said the FAA was treating the incidents as unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a coincidence that they happened one day after the next.
If you look at one incident and the other, they're not related at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Spirit gave passengers on the Friday flight vouchers for a free
round-trip anywhere in the airline's system, Moreland said. Those
on board the second returned flight got a $100 coupon for use
against a future flight, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ==
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: http://www.spiritair.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
