<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnia Holds Municipal Election  </HEADLINE>
By AIDA CERKEZ-ROBINSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- Most Serbs and Croats backed
nationalist parties, but urban Muslims voted for moderates more
supportive of reconciliation, according to partial results Monday
of weekend municipal elections.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Social Democrats, who favor working with Serbs
and Croats, won most Muslim-dominated major cities, in 25 percent
of Bosnia's municipalities in the results released by the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But the figures also showed the Serb Democratic Party, once
headed by war crimes suspect Radovan Karadzic, winning the most
votes in the Serb half of Bosnia and the Croats voting also largely
for nationalists who led them during the 1992-95 war. The Croats
share their area with the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   The grip of three nationalist parties is seen as the main
obstacle to its progress in Bosnia, where fighting ended under the
U.S.-brokered Dayton accords of November 21, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Out of nine Serb municipalities in traditionally hard-line
eastern Bosnia, the Serb Democratic Party was leading in eight. The
runner-up there appeared to be the party of pro-western Prime
Minister Milorad Dodik.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials downplayed continued Serb and Croat support of
the nationalists who helped start the war, emphasizing the gains by
moderates in Muslim regions in the second postwar municipal
elections with a turnout estimated by international observers of 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Miller, the U.S. ambassador to Bosnia, spoke of ''a new
age and a new era'' ushered in by the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But former Premier Haris Silajdzic, who heads one of the main
parties in Muslim-controlled areas, spoke of a ''negative result''
of the elections.
</P>
<P>
   He said nationalist parties ''have been reaffirmed'' in areas
they control which are the places most of the refugees should
return to but won't.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is very difficult to ensure that people return to
municipalities in which the local government will remain for the
next four years in the hands of those parties that expelled them,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Democrats won in Sarajevo, the Tuzla area, the
eastern city of Gorazde and in Bihac to the northwest, results
showed.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials said although nationalists were the choice of
Bosnian Serbs and Croats, the Social Democrats' success in Muslim
areas creates a momentum for parliamentary and presidential
elections this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Despite massive foreign investment, Bosnia's unemployment rate
is over 60 percent, and some 1.2 million people cannot return to
their prewar homes mainly because of their ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   Zlatko Lagumdzija, leader of the Social Democrats was upbeat
about his party's gains in Muslim areas. ''This is the biggest
political turn since (the) Dayton'' accords, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
