<HEADLINE> Report: Putin To Meet British Queen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin is to meet Queen
Elizabeth II when he visits London next week, a news agency
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian and British sides have agreed in principle that
Putin's itinerary will include a visit to Buckingham Palace on
April 17, the ITAR-Tass news agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin is to meet with British Prime Minister Tony Blair and
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook before meeting the queen, ITAR-Tass
said.
</P>
<P>
   In London, however, 10 Downing St. said the Tass report was
incorrect and that Prime Minister Tony Blair's office could not say
whether Putin would meet the queen. Details of the visit are yet to
be finalized.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen at the Kremlin would not comment on the report. Queen
Elizabeth, who is distantly related to the Romanov imperial family,
visited Russia in 1994 and met with President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin press service said on Monday that Putin will meet
with newly elected Japanese Prime Minster Yoshiro Mori in St.
Petersburg on April 29.
</P>
<P>
   Mori became prime minister last Wednesday after his predecessor
Keizo Obuchi suffered a stroke and slipped into a coma on April 2.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi had been eager to negotiate a peace treaty with Russia. A
territorial dispute over Russian-controlled islands north of Japan
has blocked the two nations from signing a treaty at the end of
World War II.
</P>
</TEXT>
