<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Megan's mother, Senate president back amendment to put sex offenderdetails online  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Saying courts have restricted the law
bearing her daughter's name, Maureen Kanka joined lawmakers Monday
in calling for a constitutional amendment that would allow the
state to widely expand Megan's Law.
</P>
<P>
   First proposed by the Whitman administration last month, the
amendment will be introduced into the state Senate on May 4, giving
the Legislature time to pass it so voters can have their say in
November, said Senate President Donald T. DiFrancesco, R-Union.
</P>
<P>
   Although its text does not name the Internet, legislators said
the measure would give them the authority to pass other laws
specifically allowing details about sex offenders to be posted
online. Without the amendment, any measure to broaden the community
notifications allowed by Megan's Law will likely not meet judicial
approval, supporters say.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no doubt that the constitutional amendment and any
legislation that will follow will enable parents to have better
access to the information that will help them protect their
children,'' Kanka said at a news conference. ''I have no doubt the
parents in the state of New Jersey will support this.''
</P>
<P>
   Every state has some form of sex offender notification law and
roughly half have some access to that information electronically,
DiFrancesco said. Ten states allow law enforcement online access
while 19 have, or plan to have, that information open to the
general public, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This amendment will bring our state into the 21st century,''
DiFrancesco said, adding that New Jersey would be the first state
to ''constitutionally guarantee its children protection from sexual
predators.''
</P>
<P>
   Details about who gets on the Internet list and how it will
present the information will be up to individual bills once the
amendment is passed, DiFrancesco said. The Assembly passed its
version of a bill to create an Internet registry last month.
</P>
<P>
   Kanka, now an activist for such public notification, says
parents in other states have learned of the presence of convicted
sex offenders through online registries. But state and federal
courts have so limited New Jersey's version of the law that such
notifications would be outlawed, Kanka said. The law was passed
after Megan Kanka was raped and murdered in July 1994 by a neighbor
with a record of sex crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just absolutely ridiculous. The original intent of the
law is not there,'' Kanka said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers have criticized the amendment, saying it allows
the state to broadcast what courts have said is private information
about offenders. Lawyers also contend that the state amendment will
not protect Megan's Law from a federal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands after nearly six years of court review, Megan's Law
groups convicted sex offenders into three levels, based on the
perceived risk of reoffending that they present.
</P>
<P>
   For those labeled most at risk of committing another crime, the
law allows prosecutors to provide an offender's name, address and
photo to residents living in a carefully defined area. All
offenders are required to register with police once out of prison.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a federal court judge threatened to shut down the
notifications, claiming that private information about sex
offenders became widely public. Attorney General John J. Farmer Jr.
revised the guidelines to require people who get the notices to
sign promises not to discuss the information.
</P>
<P>
   If the constitutional amendment is passed, that will sway the
federal courts, DiFrancesco said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The input of the public is very much a factor in a decision by
a federal judge,'' the Senate president said.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from Gov. Christie Whitman again offered her support
for the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ''New Jersey led the way in protecting its citizens from
potentially dangerous sex offenders when it adopted Megan's Law. It
is now time for us to use the latest technology to provide broader
access to sex offender information so the public can take
appropriate precautions,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
