<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatian President Submits Proposal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- President Stipe Mesic presented an expert
team's proposal Monday on curtailing his authority, which would
still leave him with a key role in the government.
</P>
<P>
   Mesic and Prime Minister Ivica Racan pledged in their election
campaigns earlier this year to reduce the wide-ranging presidential
powers that late President Franjo Tudjman used and abused to
install virtually one-man rule.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cabinet and Mesic appear to disagree on how many of the
president's current powers should be ceded to parliament, raising
tensions between Mesic and Racan.
</P>
<P>
   According to Croatian television, Mesic's team, composed of
former Constitutional Court justices and other legal experts,
suggested that the president remain supreme commander of the army,
participate in creating foreign policy and retain the right to
appoint the chiefs of secret services.
</P>
<P>
   According to the current constitution, the president can also
dissolve parliament, fire the prime minister and issue decrees with
the force of law.
</P>
<P>
   The Cabinet is believed to be drafting its own proposal of
constitutional changes, but its contents have not been made public.
</P>
<P>
   Once the legal changes are agreed upon, parliament will have to
adopt them with a two-thirds majority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
