<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals court divided on porch search, sending case to SupremeCourt  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A controversial 1998 drug arrest in a
high-crime neighborhood of Trenton is on its way to the state
Supreme Court to test when police can bother a man sitting on his
porch.
</P>
<P>
   Trenton police arrested Drew Johnson after spotting him stuffing
a bag into a hole on a porch where he was sitting. They found crack
cocaine in the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Andrew Smithson threw out the evidence against
Johnson because he said police had no basis to bother and search
him since he was just sitting on his porch. Police were acting on
an anonymous tip that Johnson was dealing drugs but the judge said
they have to see suspicious activity for themselves first before
arresting or searching someone.
</P>
<P>
   A state appeals court on Monday upheld Smithson's ruling but the
court was divided 2-1. This means Mercer County prosecutor Daniel
Giaquinto has an automatic right to appeal the ruling to the state
Supreme Court, which spokeswoman Emily Hornaday said he will do.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson arrest touched on a tricky area of law when police
base their actions on anonymous tips, which courts have held can be
of limited reliability. Such tips must either be highly specific
about an offense or police must limit their use of the tip to begin
a surveillance, taking no action until they themselves witness
criminal or suspicious activity.
</P>
<P>
   Trenton police on patrol in a high-crime area received a tip
from an unidentified resident on the street that Johnson was
dealing drugs. They spotted Johnson sitting on his porch and
noticed that as Johnson saw them he moved a small bag by his side
to conceal it. The officers approached him, asked him to step away
and one of them retrieved the bag with the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Judges Howard Keskin and Dorothea Wefing in a joint opinion
said, ''There was not enough in what the police saw, without more,
to establish the requisite basis for determining criminal activity
was afoot that would validate their conduct in securing defendant
or engaging in the search they undertook.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Where the police only witnessed defendant's presence on the
porch and saw him place an object beside himself, there is no
adequate basis for the action they took,'' the judges said.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Isaiah Steinberg in his dissent said the officer who
found the drugs ''believed defendant was attempting to conceal
narcotics, which was a reasonable assumption based on the totality
of the circumstances then known to him.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, a divided state Supreme Court threw out a drug
conviction in Elizabeth when it found police acting on a tip from
an informant had failed to ascertain for themselves that criminal
activity was occurring.
</P>
<P>
   ''Independent corroboration is necessary to ratify the
informant's veracity and the truthfulness of the tip,'' the court
majority said. But the vote was close with the court divided 4-3.
Chief Justice Deborah Poritz dissented, and two of the justices in
that four-vote majority, Alan Handler and Stewart Pollock, have
since retired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
