<HEADLINE> Leaders Negotiate Sale To China  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD ISRAEL AIR FORCE ONE (AP) -- Israeli and U.S. officials
are negotiating the terms of an Israeli sale of military technology
to China that the United States has opposed, a senior Israeli
official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, speaking aboard a plane carrying Prime Minister
Ehud Barak to a meeting with President Clinton, acknowledged that
the Israeli sale of planes equipped with the PHALCON radar system
would be on the agenda as the Israeli technology is apparently
based in part on U.S. research.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has asked Barak to stop the sale of the planes
that some say could undermine stability in Asia and pose a threat
to Taiwan, a U.S. ally in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are talks on a professional level,'' between U.S. and
Israeli officials, said the official who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ''We are not worried about U.S. pressure but we
understand U.S. sensitivities. The problem will work itself out.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Barak has resisted U.S. pressure. Last week, he told
visiting Defense Secretary William Cohen that Israel was required
by contract to go through with the sale of the first
PHALCON-equipped plane, though he left open the possibility of
coordinating future deals with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Israel army radio reported Monday that Barak would propose a
compromise to Clinton. Under the plan, Israel would go ahead with
the sale of the first plane, an Ilyushin-50, but would indefinitely
postpone the sale of other aircraft, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the report, Barak's office said in a statement:
''The issue will be discussed by officials from both sides, but a
decision on the matter has not yet been made.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak is meeting Clinton principally to discuss ways of spurring
forward the sputtering Mideast peace process. He returns Wednesday
to greet Chinese President Jiang Zemin in Jerusalem who is coming
on a state visit.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the speaker of the Chinese parliament, Li
Peng, and Chinese Defense Minister Chi Hoatian have visited Israel.
Chi visited Israel Aircraft Industries, which is equipping the
Ilyushin plane with the PHALCON system.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with China poses a dilemma for Barak. On the one hand,
China is a lucrative market for Israel's struggling arms industry.
On the other hand, Israel is wary of alienating its most important
ally, the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The respected Haaretz daily wrote in an editorial Monday that
Israel must not jeopardize its special relationship with
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Israeli interest is to maintain commercial relations with
China -- including military exports -- as long as such trade does not
harm American support for much more critical issues: the peace
process and compensation for the evacuation of territories that
results from that process,'' Haaretz wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
