<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Opens Crime Conference in Vienna  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- From forced labor and prostitution to
smuggling drugs and arms, transnational crime is threatening
legitimate businesses and the stability of entire nations, U.N.
Deputy Secretary-General Louise Frechette said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the 10th U.N. Conference on the Prevention of
Crime and the Treatment of Offenders, Frechette said it was more
important than ever to bring together governments, professional
crime fighters and other key players because of criminal
opportunities created by globalization.
</P>
<P>
   ''If criminals are going global, those fighting them must also
launch a global effort and create effective networks of technical,
legal and judicial cooperation, or they will always be one step
behind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Frechette said the Vienna congress and treaties like the U.N.
Convention against Transnational Organized Crime, which delegates
will be focusing on during the week, ''are definitely steps in the
right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   While globalization has had many positive effects, she said,
some people ''have jumped on the bandwagon of globalization to
create transnational criminal networks, and so to boost profits
from a wide range of illegal activities.''
</P>
<P>
   ''To them, opening borders means it is easier to traffic in
women and children for forced labor and prostitution, to smuggle
drugs and arms, and to escape justice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pino Arlacchi, head of the U.N. Office for Drug Control and
Crime Prevention, said money-launderers in particular had managed
to take advantage of the digital revolution to hide their
ill-gotten gains.
</P>
<P>
   ''Money-laundering is by no means a new form of crime, but it
now thrives in a world of electronic banking,'' he said. ''Dirty
money should find no shelter anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The congress attended by some 2,000 government officials and
experts ends next Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-10-00 1859 </TRAILER>
