<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Deplore Lack of Literature  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- The venerated Academie Francaise is on the warpath
again, this time deploring the decline of literature studies in
French high schools.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the watchdog of French language and culture released
a statement railing against a trend it says is on the verge of
wiping out literary appreciation in the land of Victor Hugo and
Moliere.
</P>
<P>
   ''First, the ancient languages were asphyxiated. One had
forgotten that they help to learn French. Today, language and
literature itself seem to have become the enemies we must
destroy,'' the statement read.
</P>
<P>
   The decline of literature courses over the past two decades ''is
on the verge of completely eliminating knowledge and appreciation
of literature,'' the 40 members of the Academie, known as the
Immortals, said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Academie Francaise was founded by Cardinal Richelieu, Louis
XIII's influential finance minister, in 1635 not only to ''clean
out the garbage from the mouths of common folk'' but also to rein
in the nation's elite thinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the elite body has been a ferocious defender of the
purity of the French language, decrying the creeping introduction
of Franglais, a mixture of French and English, and the invasion of
new English words from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Their latest foray in the defense of literature is addressed to
President Jacques Chirac, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and the
culture and education ministers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is now possible to get as far as (a high school diploma)
without ever having read in full any of our great classics,'' the
sages bemoaned. ''It is to despair of schools to say that in
principal they are unable to initiate children and adults of
different origins into the pleasure of understanding our literary
masterpieces.''
</P>
<P>
   The Academie said modern education methods were robbing teaching
of all content ''to the point where there no longer exists any
criteria of excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Ideological egalitarianism reinforces inequalities,'' the
Immortals said, arguing that students who really want to learn take
privileged and selective courses which are only available to richer
families.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a strange idea of citizenship to want it to be ignorant
of the meditation on man that has been the subject of our
literature during 1,000 years and continues to be today,'' the
statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-10-00 1901 </TRAILER>
