<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Florio campaign rips Corzine over Sudan investments  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The attacks became international Monday in
the Democratic primary campaign for U.S. Senate as former Gov. Jim
Florio's campaign accused opponent Jon Corzine of profiting on
slavery and civil war in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jon Corzine is a beneficiary of slave oil, slave money, blood
money'' because of his role at Goldman Sachs when the investment
firm financed an oil venture in Sudan. The U.S. State Department
has condemned the Islamic government for its ties to terrorism, its
conduct of a civil war and its inaction on famine.
</P>
<P>
   The Corzine campaign refuted the charge in a news statement,
claiming that the financing of Talisman Energy of Canada provided
no direct benefit to the government of Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The Corzine campaign also issued a counterpunch, saying that
when Florio was a senior partner at the Mudge Rose law firm, it
represented the Philippine government and a trade association in
Columbia, two nations the Corzine campaign linked with child labor
and anti-union violence.
</P>
<P>
   Florio campaign aide Walter Fields did not deny the claims of
the Corzine campaign and said he had no specific response to it. He
said only that Florio invites scrutiny of his record against
Corzine's.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will leave it up to the voters to decide which candidate is
more qualified and more able and better prepared to serve their
interests,'' Fields said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine was co-chairman of Goldman Sachs from 1994 to 1999. He
left the firm with a fortune estimated at $300 million, including
millions of shares in the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Florio became a senior partner at Mudge Rose after losing in
1993 to Gov. Christie Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Fields said the attacks are justified because Corzine has made
an issue of his career at Goldman Sachs in helping the economy. He
said Talisman Energy has propped up the Sudanese government and was
the lynchpin of oil development there.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a real contradiction in the public face of Jon Corzine
and the private face of Jon Corzine, first during his tenure at
Goldman Sachs and now as one the largest shareholders of that
company,'' Fields said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you are going to ask the people of New Jersey to judge you
on your record at Goldman Sachs, if you are going to take credit
for creating jobs, then we want to talk about the entire record,
and this is part of the record,'' Fields said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States severed diplomatic relations with Sudan in
1996 amid growing anti-U.S. sentiment and the Islamic government's
war against factions in the southern part of the desert nation.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey recently joined the list of states that have
withdrawn investments from Talisman Energy.
</P>
<P>
   In February, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright
issued her most recent condemnation of Sudan, accusing its military
of a Feb. 8 bombing attack that killed 14 children at a Catholic
school in the Nuba Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The Corzine campaign in a news statement said the Goldman Sachs
deal to help finance Talisman Energy ''established a firewall to
make sure the proceeds from both transactions were not used for
anything related to the Sudan ... and was not used, and will not be
used, to fund the Sudan or any Sudanese entity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
