<HEADLINE> Pulitzer Prize Winners in Brief  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The 2000 Pulitzer Prizes for Arts:
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRAMA
</P>
<P>
   Donald Margulies, ''Dinner With Friends''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Margulies, winner of the 2000 Pulitzer Prize for drama
for ''Dinner With Friends,'' has had a successful career
off-Broadway with many of those plays first done in nonprofit
theaters in New York and around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dinner With Friends'' tells the story of a seemingly happy
couple who question their relationship after their best friends
decide to divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ''The play emerged out of a particular time in my life, a
mid-life reflection, on the pains of fidelity, friendship and
sexual passion,'' he said Monday. It has been running at the
Variety Arts Theater off-Broadway since November.
</P>
<P>
   His other plays include ''Collected Stories,'' ''Sight Unseen,''
''The Loman Family Picnic,'' ''What's Wrong With This Picture?' and
''Found a Peanut.''
</P>
<P>
   Margulies, born Sept. 2, 1952, in Brooklyn, N.Y., graduated from
the State University of New York-Purchase with a degree in visual
arts. He lives in New Haven, Conn., and teaches playwriting at the
Yale School of Drama.
</P>
<P>
   FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Jhumpa Lahiri, ''Interpreter of Maladies''
</P>
<P>
   Three factors make Jhumpa Lahiri an unlikely winner of the
Pulitzer Prize for fiction: She's young (32), a first-time author
and a writer of short stories. But the New York City resident was
still honored Monday for her collection ''Interpreter of
Maladies,'' beating out National Book Award winner Ha Jin and past
Pulitzer winner Annie Proulx.
</P>
<P>
   Lahiri is a London native who grew up in Rhode Island and
majored in English at Barnard College. She's been writing since
childhood and has had an especially happy relationship with The New
Yorker, which has published her stories, named her one of the best
young American writers and gave her an award for best debut book.
Lahiri also recently won the PEN/Hemingway award for first fiction.
</P>
<P>
   The nine stories in ''Interpreter of Maladies'' are set in both
India and the United States and center on people with Indian
backgrounds. The book, published as a paperback, has sold more than
40,000 copies, a high number for a collection of stories.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Spratlan, ''Life Is a Dream, Opera in Three Acts: Act Two,
Concert Version''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Spratlan, born Sept. 5, 1940, in Miami, has written for
orchestra, voice and piano, voice and instruments, chamber works,
choral pieces, ballet scores and one opera, ''Life Is a Dream,''
which won the 2000 Pulitzer Prize for music.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a 17th-century play by Pedro Calderon, it was
commissioned in the mid-1970s by the New Haven Opera Theater, which
went out of business before Spratlan finished it. The opera has
never been produced.
</P>
<P>
   The composer used a commission for the Boston new music group,
Dinosaur Annex Music Ensemble, to prepare Act 2 of his opera for
performance in concert. It was performed twice in January.
</P>
<P>
   Spratlan hopes winning the Pulitzer will put a new spotlight on
''Life Is a Dream'' so that an opera company will produce it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's nice to have the honor but that would be the real
significance of this prize,'' Spratlan said.
</P>
<P>
   He studied at Yale University, under Mel Powell and Gunther
Schuller. Spratlan taught at Penn State University before joining
the faculty of Amherst College in Massachusetts, where he was made
professor in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   BIOGRAPHY
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Schiff, ''Vera: (Mrs. Vladimir Nabokov): Portrait of a
Marriage''
</P>
<P>
   ''Vera: (Mrs. Vladimir Nabokov): Portrait of a Marriage,''
winner of the 2000 Pulitzer Prize for biography, was Stacy Schiff's
second book.
</P>
<P>
   A former senior editor at Simon &AMP; Schuster, Schiff was educated
at Phillips Academy and Williams College in Massachusetts.
''Saint-Exupery: A Biography,'' her first effort, was a Pulitzer
Prize finalist in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''Vera'' looks at the relationship and literary partnership
between Vera Nabokov and her husband, Vladimir, the celebrated
author of ''Lolita'' and ''Pale Fire.'' The book was published last
April by Random House.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff, who has written for The New Yorker, The Times Literary
Supplement and The New York Times Book Review, lives in New York
City and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   POETRY
</P>
<P>
   Charles Kenneth Williams, ''Repair''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Kenneth Williams received the poetry Pulitzer for a
collection titled ''Repair,'' meditations on hurt and healing that
touch on topics including the Holocaust and American race
relations.
</P>
<P>
   The 63-year-old Williams, who was born in Newark, N.J., teaches
creative writing, poetry and dramatic adaptation and translation at
Princeton University.
</P>
<P>
   The poet, who graduated from the University of Pennsylvania in
1959, will shortly publish a memoir called ''Misgivings,'' about
his family and growing up in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' ''Flesh and Blood'' (1987) won the National Book
Critics Circle Award, and ''The Vigil'' (1996) was nominated for a
Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   John W. Dower, ''Embracing Defeat: Japan in the Wake of World
War II''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Providence, R.I., John W. Dower is considered one of
the nation's top historians of modern Japan. His ''Embracing
Defeat: Japan in the Wake of World War II,'' co-published by W.W.
Norton &AMP; Co., and The New Press, offers a compelling portrait of
the shaping of contemporary Japan. The book also won the National
Book Award.
</P>
<P>
   Dower, 65, who teaches Japanese history at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, received his Ph.D. in History and Far
Eastern Languages from Harvard University in 1972, and a B.A. in
American Studies from Amherst College.
</P>
<P>
   His other books include ''War Without Mercy: Race and Power in
the Pacific War'' (1986), which won the National Book Critics
Circle Award for nonfiction, and the Masayoshi Ohira Memorial Prize
in Japan; ''Empire and Aftermath: Yoshida Shigeru and the Japanese
Experience, 1878-1954'' (1974); and ''Japan in War and Peace:
Selected Essays'' (1994).
</P>
<P>
   ''Hellfire: A Journey From Hiroshima,'' a documentary Dower
produced with John Junkerman about artists Iri and Toshi Maruki ,
was nominated for an Academy Award in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Dower and his wife, Yasuko, have lived in Massachusetts as well
as Tokyo, Kyoto and Kanazawa, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   David M. Kennedy, ''Freedom From Fear: The American People in
Depression and War, 1929-1945''
</P>
<P>
   David M. Kennedy, a professor of history at Stanford University,
was a Pulitzer finalist for his 1980 book, ''Over Here: The First
World War and American Society.'' His ''Birth Control in America:
The Career of Margaret Sanger'' (1970) won a Bancroft Prize.
</P>
<P>
   ''Freedom From Fear: The American People in Depression and War,
1929-1945,'' published by the Oxford University Press, took Kennedy
11 years to complete. The massive volume -- 936 pages -- examines the
Depression and war years and the role of Franklin Roosevelt and the
New Deal, and chronicles America's emergence as an affluent
society.
</P>
<P>
   To get a feel for a sense of place for his book, Kennedy, 58,
visited a number of battlefields, including Guadalcanal in the
Solomon Islands and Anzio in Italy. He also visited Normandy beach
during the 50th anniversary of D-Day in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy has a Ph.D. and an M.A. in American Studies from Yale
University, and a B.A. in history from Stanford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-10-00 1918 </TRAILER>
