<HEADLINE> Ticket Arrest Prompts Lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- A day before the Boston Red Sox home opener, a
federal judge Monday ordered police not to arrest people who are
selling tickets outside Fenway Park at or below face value.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Joseph Tauro ruled in the case of Gary A.
Lainer, a veterinarian who sued police. Lainer said he was trying
to resell an $18 ticket he had for face value last year when he was
arrested and manhandled by Boston officers.
</P>
<P>
   ''This means that ordinary citizens ... should be able to resell
tickets at face value or less without worrying about being arrested
by the police,'' said Bob Mendillo, Lainer's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Tauro granted Lainer's request for a preliminary injunction.
Mendillo said Lainer's lawsuit against the police and the city
would continue, with Lainer seeking to get class-action status and
seeking damages.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they would comply with the decision while
considering an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, department officials also said they would
continue to arrest scalpers ''when the officer has probable cause
to believe that the suspect has attempted to unlawfully inflate the
ticket price.''
</P>
</TEXT>
