<HEADLINE> Columbine Coverage Wins Pulitzers  </HEADLINE>
By COLLEEN SLEVIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- There were a few cheers but mostly there were hugs
and tears in the newsrooms of Denver's two newspapers Monday as
their staffs were named Pulitzer Prize winners for their coverage
of the Columbine High School massacre.
</P>
<P>
   At the Denver Rocky Mountain News, staff members held a moment
of silence for the victims who died when two students opened fire
in the school April 20.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the hardest things about today is that 15 people died.
And it's just part of our jobs that all we can do is cover it,''
said John Temple, the newspaper's editor and vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocky Mountain News won the Pulitzer Prize in the breaking
news photography category for pictures taken after the attack. The
Denver Post won for breaking news reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-four reporters, eight photographers and five artists --
nearly the entire Post staff -- were on the story the first day, and
many of the details they collected in the hours after the attack
came to figure prominently in the investigation of the deadliest
school shooting in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the biggest prize in journalism, but because it's for
covering one of the most unimaginable tragedies, it's a shame,''
said Jeanette Chavez, the Post's managing editor.
</P>
<P>
   About three dozen journalists huddled around a speaker phone in
the Post newsroom to listen to the announcements, erupting in a
brief cheer when the newspaper's name was read. Gerald Grilly,
president and publisher, said the tragedy had taken an emotional
toll on his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a shame that you have to be recognized for a tragedy like
Columbine,'' Grilly said. ''But it shows you the role of newspapers
in getting information out to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   In a subdued Rocky Mountain News newsroom, Photography Director
Janet Reeves said it was difficult to win an award for the
Columbine photographs, but it was an important milestone for
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel it's our job to tell the story the best way we can. I
hope the work we did helped explain to the world what happened here
and what they lost,'' said Reeves, who began her career as a photo
technician at the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Photographer Ken Papaleo, who has worked for the paper for 20
years, recalled having to use auto focus to take photographs during
the funeral of slain student Matt Kechter because he was crying
during the service.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to the newsroom, he said he was grateful that
editors respected his wish not to use some of the intimate images
he had captured of Kechter's grieving parents.
</P>
<P>
   Both newspapers plan to donate their $5,000 prizes to the HOPE
fund, which was established to rebuild Columbine's library, where
10 of the victims and the two gunmen died. The Post plans to donate
an additional $5,000 to the fund to match the prize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-10-00 2003 </TRAILER>
