<HEADLINE> Israel Pressing For Accounting of Jews  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Israel pressed Argentina on
Monday to investigate the disappearances of thousands of Jews
during the 1976-83 military dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Deputy Foreign Minister Nawaf Massalha said he raised
the issue in talks here with Argentine President Fernando De la Rua
and would discuss it further in meetings with officials Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our government thinks that, as a country, we should press to
know what happened to them,'' Massalha told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   At least 9,000 leftists and dissidents vanished after being
detained by the military junta's security forces, according to an
Argentine government report. Human rights groups say the figure is
closer to 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Of those who vanished, up to 2,000 were Jewish, Israel-based
Jewish groups say. Groups in Argentina estimate the number to be
approximately 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Families of the disappeared say Jewish dissidents were regularly
singled out for especially cruel treatment during Argentina's
''dirty war.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Argentina's top junta leaders were sentenced to life in
prison after public trials found them guilty of human rights
abuses. De la Rua's predecessor, Carlos Menem, pardoned the top
junta leaders five years later.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina is home to some 300,000 Jews, the second largest
community in the Americas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-10-00 2003 </TRAILER>
