<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minnesota Reporter Wins Pulitzer  </HEADLINE>
By KARREN MILLS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- As reporters at the Saint Paul Pioneer
Press were dousing Pulitzer Prize-winning reporter George Dohrmann
in champagne to celebrate his award Monday, the university where he
uncovered academic fraud in the men's basketball program was
imposing more sanctions on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Dohrmann, 27, the lead reporter on the newspaper's series about
questionable practices in the University of Minnesota program,
wiped tears from his eyes as his colleagues broke into ''For he's a
jolly good fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   ''From when this first began, everybody was so good. When I
pitched the story, I was 25. They trusted me and just said 'go for
it.','' Dohrmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Dohrmann and his colleagues reported that a tutor did work for
student-athletes, athletes earned credits from classes they never
knew about, faculty were bullied by the basketball program staff
and the head coach told players to lie about the scope of the
cheating.
</P>
<P>
   The university spent seven months investigating before releasing
a 1,000-page report that concluded 34 of 50 allegations were true.
Twenty-eight of those involved at least one violation of National
Collegiate Athletic Association rules during nearly a decade when
Clem Haskins coached the team.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the school announced it will eliminate six
scholarships over four academic years; reduce official visits from
12 to eight for the next three academic years; reduce the number of
in-person recruiting contacts for prospective players; and cut the
number of coaches allowed to evaluate players off-campus during the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The school also will return to the NCAA 90 percent of the money
it received from the Big Ten Conference from participating in the
1993-94, 1994-95 and 1996-97 NCAA basketball tournaments with
ineligible players.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the university had banned the team from postseason play
for one year and put itself on NCAA probation for an unspecified
period of time.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA is still considering what sanctions to levy against the
university, which spent nearly $1.9 million on the basketball
probe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
