<HEADLINE> Bush Edges Ahead of Gore in Poll  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush has pulled slightly
ahead of Vice President Al Gore in a new poll on the presidential
campaign released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the likely Republican nominee, had 50 percent support in
the CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll, compared to 41 percent for Gore, the
Democrats' likely choice.
</P>
<P>
   Eight percent had no opinion and 1 percent chose the category
''other.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 502 likely voters was taken April 7-9 and had a
margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier poll taken March 30-April 2 had Bush and Gore in a
statistical tie, with 46 percent support for the Texas governor and
45 percent support for the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   A Newsweek poll on Saturday also showed the two in a
neck-and-neck race.
</P>
<P>
   In a hypothetical race with commentator Pat Buchanan as the
nominee of the Reform Party, Buchanan takes a tiny slice of voters
from Bush, who drops to 48 percent with Gore at 42 percent and
Buchanan with 4 percent support, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that a growing share of voters believe
Gore did not do anything illegal or unethical in his fund-raising
activities.
</P>
<P>
   About four in 10, or 41 percent, said Gore has not done anything
''seriously wrong.'' About one in four, or 27 percent, said he has
done ''something unethical, but not illegal,'' and 12 percent said
he has done ''something illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, the last time this question was asked, 33
percent said Gore hadn't done anything seriously wrong, 32 percent
said he did ''something unethical, but not illegal,'' and 21
percent said he had done ''something illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   On other subjects, the poll found:
</P>
<P>
   -- Sixty percent saying that 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez should be
returned to Cuba to live with his father, and 31 percent saying the
boy should remain in the United States. The results are similar to
a recent ABC News-Washington Post poll.
</P>
<P>
   -- Americans divided on the Microsoft case, in which a federal
judge said the computer software maker had engaged in
anticompetitive practices. Four in 10, or 41 percent, said they
side more with the judge, while about the same number, or 39
percent, side with Microsoft. Sixteen percent had no opinion and 4
percent were impartial.
</P>
<P>
   -- Response to the census should be high, at least if people are
telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found 82 percent saying they returned the completed
form, while 14 percent said they planned to fill it out or already
have done so but hadn't returned it. According to the Census
Bureau, only about six in 10 Americans have returned their forms.
(This question was asked of 923 people who said they have received
census forms, and has a margin of error of plus or minus 4
percentage points.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-10-00 2016 </TRAILER>
