<HEADLINE> Government Fines Serbian Television  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The leading non-government
television station was sentenced fined $40,000 Monday, and a
government minister sued an independent weekly for libel, in a
continuing crackdown against free media in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern city of Nis on Monday night, more than 10,000
people protested the recent verdict against the local Narodne
Novine newspaper, which was ordered last week to pay the equivalent
of $35,000 in a suit filed by the Yugoslav army.
</P>
<P>
   ''Red Bandits,'' shouted the flag-waving crowd, demanding the
resignation of President Slobodan Milosevic and his neo-Communist
allies.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of Serbia's main opposition parties were at the
rally and condemned growing government pressure on independent
media and pledged unity ahead of municipal and federal elections in
the country, which are due by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   At the demonstration, Aleksandar Krstic, an official in the Nis
opposition-run municipal government, called on people to resist
government pressure and defend the newspaper in case government
officials arrive to confiscate equipment and other property for
nonpayment of the fine.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, the chief of Studio B, Dragan Kojadinovic said
his station will not pay the fine stemming from a third libel suit
by a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We no longer want to take part in this judicial circus,'' said
Kojadinovic, referring to repeated fines against his station. ''The
government can now do whatever they want, but we will defend our
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Studio B, which is run by the opposition municipal government in
the capital Belgrade, has been fined several times this year.
</P>
<P>
   According to a much criticized Serbian law, the media can be
sued and fined for carrying statements critical of the government.
Dozens of media have been fined in the past several months. But
Studio B's refusal to pay could lead to the confiscation of the
station's equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Police Maj. Branko Djuric sued Studio B after the TV station
carried a statement by an opposition party alleging that the police
official was involved in an assassination attempt against the
party's leader, Vuk Draskovic.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, Serbia's minister of culture, Zeljko Simic,
filed a suit against the independent Vreme weekly for statements
published in an interview carried by the paper. Beta news agency
said that the court summons was plastered Monday evening on the
door of the Vreme offices in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The trial against Vreme will be held on Tuesday, Beta said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
