<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Firefighters Battle Toronto Blaze
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Firefighters were battling a blaze in a factory
Sunday in the city's east end that sent clouds of black smoke so
high they could be seen from across Lake Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Crews from 20 to 30 fire trucks were trying the control the
blaze which broke out about 4 p.m. in the industrial plant which
borders on a residential area.
</P>
<P>
   Police Supt. Jim Bamford said there were chemicals in the U.S.E.
Hickson plant but it was not known what kind and whether they were
toxic.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no dangers to the residents,'' said Bamford.
</P>
<P>
   There are no plans to evacuate the area, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Kirkpatrick, 23, who lives on the Lake Ontario shore
between St. Catharines and Niagara-on-the-Lake, said he noticed the
smoke about 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ''As I watched there appeared to be almost explosions as plumes
of smoke shot into the sky,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By 6:30 p.m., he said, black smoke spread from Toronto eastward
along the skyline for several kilometers
</P>
<P>
   ------
Spring Snow Slows Traffic
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Quebecers put their snow shovels to work again
on the weekend as a spring storm hit the province.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of traffic accidents were reported on provincial
highways, causing at least one death, as snow sharply cut
visibility.
</P>
<P>
   The storm hit at a time when the city had only limited
snow-removal resources available, said Christiane Bolduc, a city
official.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our contracts with private firms ended March 31,'' she said.
''So all operations are being done by city employees and city
crews.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
Canadian Alliance: Stick To Party Scripts
</P>
<P>
   KAMLOOPS, British Columbia (AP) -- Canadian Alliance leadership
candidates stuck to the party script on taxes and government
reform, but questions of God and moral values split them down the
middle during the party's first leadership forum here.
</P>
<P>
   The declared candidates for the leadership race are former
Reform party leader Preston Manning, Alberta MLA Stockwell Day,
Toronto lawyer Joe Peschisolido and British Columbia MP Keith
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The place of God in government and schools was the first
question to the four candidates from the audience of about 500.
</P>
<P>
   God ''may have an idea where Svend Robinson should go,'' Day
said Saturday as he joked about NDP MP Robinson's petition to have
God stricken from the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin and Peschisolido, the two dark horses in the Canadian
Alliance leadership race, came down strongly against a
theologically driven government.
</P>
<P>
   ''We live in a secular world and society,'' said Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hallmark of society is to be tolerant of all religions. I
believe strongly in the separation of church and state.''
</P>
<P>
   Peschisolido said he doesn't believe in imposing one's morals.
</P>
