<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Begins Committee Takeover  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive
Republican presidential nominee, began taking control of the
Republican National Committee on Monday by naming a former state
party chairman to a top RNC post.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Meyer will be chairman of the RNC Victory 2000 campaign,
RNC chairman Jim Nicholson announced.
</P>
<P>
   ''I look forward to working closely with him to unify our party,
energize our grassroots organization and deliver the Republican
Party's optimistic and hopeful message for our country's future,''
Nicholson said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer chaired the Texas GOP from 1988 to 1994, helping it
reverse years of Democratic rule. He was a senior adviser in the
failed 1996 presidential campaign of Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials noted that Meyer is close to Arizona
Sen. John McCain, a vanquished Bush rival whose endorsement is
being sought by the nominee-in-waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also moved his campaign political director, Maria Cino, to
the RNC, where she will be a deputy for political and congressional
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Johnson Phillips, one of Bush's original Texas
fund-raisers, will be deputy chairman for operations at the RNC.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had considered naming one of his oldest friends and
fund-raisers, Don Evans, to the top post but decided to keep him in
Texas, where he is a valuable senior adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's likely general election rival, Vice President Al Gore,
already has many allies at the Democratic National Committee but is
expected to bolster his presence by moving political operative
Michael Whouley to the party.
</P>
<P>
   It is traditional for nominees to shift staff to their parties,
both to reduce campaign costs and to oversee the political
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, considered a moderate Republican, did not seek a fourth
term as Texas GOP chairman after it became clear that social
conservatives had enough votes to topple him. Bush's communications
director, Karen Hughes, got her start in politics by working for
Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was making the announcements in a conference call Monday
with RNC members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
