<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Immigrants Ordered To Be Sent Home  </HEADLINE>
By BOB EGELKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Hundreds of illegal immigrants in nine
Western states who have completed prison terms for crimes in this
country must be freed until the United States can persuade their
homelands to take them back, a federal appeals court ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a 3-0 ruling, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rejected
immigration officials' argument that federal law authorizes
indefinite -- potentially lifelong -- jailing of illegal immigrants
whose native countries have no repatriation agreement with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which conflicts with decisions of two other appeals
courts, will probably be appealed, said Bill Strassberger, a
spokesman for the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our priority is to keep the community safe, and no one will be
released if they are deemed a threat to public safety,''
Strassberger said.
</P>
<P>
   The court said the aliens must be released 90 days after a final
deportation order and allowed to remain free under INS supervision
until their home country reaches an agreement with the United
States to accept deportees.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they have to face going back to their home country, it
would be a horrible injustice and a tragedy to require lockup for
five or 10 years,'' said Jay Stansell, an assistant federal public
defender in Seattle, where the case originated.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 federal law required deportation of noncitizens who
committed any of a wide range of felonies, including most types of
drug crimes. After completing their prison terms, they were to be
transferred to INS custody and deported within 90 days of a final
removal order.
</P>
<P>
   The law said immigrants whose home countries refused to accept
them ''may be detained beyond the removal period.''
</P>
<P>
   The INS contended the law allowed indefinite detention of
immigrants it considered dangerous, but the court disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Without clear authorizing language, ''courts should ordinarily
not assume that Congress intended a result as harsh and
constitutionally dubious as indefinite detention,'' Judge Stephen
Reinhardt wrote in the court's opinion. He also noted that
international law condemns ''prolonged and arbitrary detention.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling applies to immigrants from Cambodia, Vietnam and
Laos, none of which has a repatriation agreement with the United
States. It also covers some Cubans and some immigrants from the
former Soviet Union who cannot be deported to their newly
independent homelands for various reasons, Stansell said.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyer said the government has estimated that 400 to
500 immigrants would be affected in the nine states covered by the
9th Circuit, the largest of the federal appellate circuits. The INS
said a year ago that there were 3,500 such prisoners nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled in the case of Kim Ho Ma, a Cambodian refugee
who came to the United States with his family at age 2 and was
convicted of manslaughter in a Seattle drive-by shooting 15 years
later.
</P>
<P>
   He served just over two years in state prison and spent nearly
three more years in the custody of the INS, which could not deport
him to Cambodia because of the lack of a repatriation agreement but
said he was still dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Robert Lasnik ordered Ma released last
September, saying indefinite detention without charges was
unconstitutional. The appeals court sidestepped the constitutional
issue by finding that federal law did not authorize indefinite
detention.
</P>
<P>
   Ma was arrested recently in nearby Kent, Wash., for
investigation of misdemeanor assault. He was released on $1,000
bond in that case, but federal authorities will ask Lasnik to
return him to INS custody April 19 for violating the terms of his
release, said Harold Malkin, spokesman for the U.S. Attorney's
office.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The ruling is available at
http://www.ce9.uscourts.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-10-00 2157 </TRAILER>
