<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quotes From Pulitzer Prize Winners  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   ''This is astonishing. I'm going to dance around with
my wife
for a few moments.'' -- John Dower, a professor of history at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology who won the Pulitzer Prize
for general nonfiction for ''Embracing Defeat: Japan in the Wake of
World War II.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very grateful to the Pulitzer board and jurors for
recognizing the significance and the professionalism of our work.
We're proud of the No Gun Ri reporting. But our celebration is
tempered by the nature of what we confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   ''In fact, we feel the greater tributes today belong to the U.S.
Army veterans, men of conscience, who helped us, and most of all to
the Korean survivors who would not let their quest for truth die.''
-- Reporters Sang-hun Choe, Charles J. Hanley and Martha Mendoza,
and researcher Randy Herschaft, who uncovered the alleged killing
of Korean civilians by U.S. troops during the Korean War. Their
work won the Pulitzer Prize for investigative reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is one time where photos were indeed an eloquent voice
for the powerless and clearly influenced world opinion.'' -- Carol
Guzy, one of three Washington Post photographers who won the prize
for feature photography for pictures of Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course I'm thrilled and this is an incredible moment for
the Village Voice, and I'm on Cloud Nine. But for the people that I
reported on, unfortunately nothing has changed.'' -- Village Voice
reporter Mark Schoofs, who won the international reporting prize
for a series on the AIDS crisis in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll think of it as a day The Washington Post set a small
stone down in the dirt of an unmarked grave.'' -- Washington Post
reporter Katherine Boo, who won the public service gold medal for
stories disclosing neglect and abuse in group homes for the
mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''This shows that a newspaper willing to take a hard look at a
serious subject, and devote a tremendous amount of resources to
something that is of tremendous importance to our culture, is
rewarded for taking on a significant subject,'' Eric Newhouse of
the Great Falls (Mont.) Tribune, who won the prize for explanatory
reporting for stories on alcohol abuse and the problems it creates
in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''From when this first began, everybody was so good. When I
pitched the story, I was 25. They trusted me and just said 'go for
it.''' -- Reporter George Dohrmann of the St. Paul (Minn.) Pioneer
Press, who won for beat reporting for stories about academic fraud
at the University of Minnesota men's basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''I gave up wine for Lent, but I think I'm going to give myself
a dispensation.'' -- David M. Kennedy, who won the history prize for
''Freedom from Fear: The American People in Depression and War,
1929-45.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''This room is full of people who know all the stuff I've lifted
from them.'' -- Washington Post feature writer Henry Allen, who won
the criticism award for articles critiquing photography exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess I want to thank President Clinton for doing so much
for the cause of political journalism. Had I known what he would do
for columnists in 1992, I might have voted for him.'' -- Paul Gigot
of The Wall Street Journal, who won the commentary award for
columns on politics and government.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I'm going to get outside and take a walk.'' -- Stacy
Schiff, winner of the biography prize for ''Vera (Mrs. Vladimir
Nabokov),'' who is nine months pregnant and on bed rest.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''The play emerged out of a particular time in my life, a
midlife reflection on the pains of fidelity, friendship and sexual
passion.'' -- Playwright Donald Margulies, winner of the drama prize
for his off-Broadway play ''Dinner With Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   ''If, on the strength of the Pulitzer, I'm able to have a
successful production of 'Life Is a Dream,' I would love to write
another opera.'' -- Lewis Spratlan, winner for music, whose winning
work has never been produced. ''I wouldn't do it on speculation.
That's too much of a heartbreak.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   ''We were actually joking about the Pulitzer Prize yesterday.''
-- Jhumpa Lahiri, winner of the fiction prize. ''At the
(PEN/Hemingway) awards dinner a friend of the family's said, 'The
Nobel is next.' Ha. Ha. And somebody else said, 'No, no, the
Pulitzers come before that.' We were just laughing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   ''They were very happy.'' -- Poetry prize winner Charles Kenneth
Williams in his class at Princeton University, where students
applauded him. ''I'm a little speechless. It feels nice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
