<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monday's Baseball Notes  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Twins-Royals:
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: During Ron Coomer's at-bat in the fourth, a fan in
the upper deck had an embarrassing moment. Coomer flared a foul
ball into the stands and when the fan lunged for the ball, his red
jacket fell off and went sailing into the crowd below. While people
laughed and applauded, ushers retrieved the jacket and returned it
to him. ... Jacque Jones, whose two-run homer tied it 5-5, tried to
be philosophical about the loss, saying, ''That's baseball. It's
going to happen again. Maybe next time it will happen to the other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The Jumbotron behind left field was not working due
to technical problems. A team official said the needed part was not
available in Kansas City and had to be ordered from out of state.
The Royals put in a rush order, hoping to get the Jumbotron working
in time for Cal Ripken Jr.'s drive toward 3,000 hits, which resumes
when the Orioles visit Tuesday and Wednesday. Ripken, who's six
hits away, also marked two other career milestones in Kansas City.
On Aug. 10, 1981 he made his major league debut in Royals Stadium,
and in 1996 he played in his 2,216th consecutive game, breaking
Sachio Kinugasa's world major league record.
Indians-Athletics:
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: In the midst of a season-high offensive performance
by the Indians, Jim Thome had a tough night at the plate Sunday.
While the Indians completed a three-game sweep by defeating Tampa
Bay 17-4, Thome struck out five times, tying a club and major
league record. The only other Indians players to fan five times in
a game were Larry Doby on April 25, 1948, and Rick Manning on May
15, 1977. Thome became the 37th major leaguer to strike out five
times in a game and the first since Scott Rolen last Aug. 23. ...
The Indians have been second best in a manner of speaking. Heading
into Monday night's game at Oakland, the Indians had outscored
opponents 23-4 in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: 2B Randy Velarde, who began the season on the 15-day DL
with a strained left knee, had his first light workout Monday.
Velarde did some light jogging, hit about 40 baseballs off a tee
and played catch. There's still no word on when he'll return. ...
In the meantime, Oakland manager Art Howe said. In the meantime,
Howe said the A's have been happy with rookie Frank Menechino's
play in Velarde's absence. Menechino has fielded well and was
batting .211 before Monday night, with two homers and four RBIs.
... The A's patience at the plate is showing up again. Oakland drew
a season-high 10 walks in a 14-2 victory over the White Sox on
Sunday and were tied for the league lead with 31 walks before
Monday's games. Last year, the A's led the majors with an Oakland
team-record 770 walks. Last season's walks total also was the
fifth-most in major league history.
Blue Jays-Angels:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: The Blue Jays were 9-3 against the Angels last season,
winning all six of their games in Toronto. ... Blue Jays manger Jim
Fregosi recently was selected to the Angels' all-time team as both
the manager and shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: Benji Gil started in place of Gary DiSarcina at SS for
the second straight game. DiSarcina bruised his left thumb Saturday
making a diving catch and is listed as day to day. ... Mo Vaughn,
who donated money to benefit the University of Irvine Medical
Center for every RBI he had last season, will be honored by having
a play center named after him this week, the Mo Vaughn Child Life
Playroom.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Marlins-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Preston Wilson extended his hitting streak to eight
games with a third-inning single. Wilson hit just .192 in spring
training. ... Manager John Boles moved former All-Star shortstop
Alex Gonzalez up from eighth to seventh in the batting order.
Gonzalez was banished to the end of the order because of
continually lackadaisical play, including his failure to field an
important grounder in Florida's Saturday loss to Colorado. ...
Marlins owner John Henry was expected to meet with baseball
commissioner Bud Selig in Milwaukee about Florida's ongoing quest
for a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Brewers play-by-play broadcaster and Wisconsin
man-about-town Bob Uecker rode onto the field on a Harley and threw
out the first pitch in the final home opener at County Stadium. ...
The opening day festivities also included a giant American flag
unfurled in the outfield and a flyover by two F-16 jets from the
115th fighter wing in Madison. ... Manager Davey Lopes, third
baseman Jose Hernandez, catcher Henry Blanco and starting pitcher
Jimmy Haynes all made their home debuts with the Brewers. Lopes
received a warm ovation from the large opening-day crowd. ... Lopes
had trouble finding his way to County Stadium for the club's home
opener. ''I thought I was going the wrong way down Bluemound
Road,'' Lopes admitted. ''I said, 'Where's the stadium?' I was
getting ready to go into a gas station and ask where County Stadium
is. I kind of started doubting myself there for a minute.''
Braves-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Andres Galarraga, who hit a two-run homer Monday,
credits Don Baylor, his manager in Colorado, with reviving his
career. Galarraga won the NL Silver Slugger Award in 1988 and hit
20 home runs in 1988, '89 and '90. But by 1991, his average had
dropped to .219 and he hit only nine homers. He signed with the
expansion Rockies in 1993, and hit .370 his first season in
Colorado. ''I can say he was like a father,'' Galarraga said of
Baylor, whom he greeted with a hug before the game. ''He helped me
to turn my career around, both with hitting and the mental part of
the game.'' ... Kerry Ligtenberg gave up his first run of the
season on Shane Andrew's three-run, game-tying homer. Ligtenberg,
who missed all of last season after a ligament was replaced in his
right elbow, had given up just one hit in his first two games. ...
Chipper Jones has had at least one hit in each of Atlanta's first
seven games. He was 1-for-4 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: The Cubs optioned RHP Matt Karchner to Triple-A Iowa
after the game and recalled RHP Ruben Quevedo. ... Thanks to the
55,000 who attended the Cubs ''home'' game in Japan, Chicago's home
attendance is already at 93,655 after two games. ... Rookie LHP
Scott Downs earned himself another start Friday after Sunday's
outing in Cincinnati. In his major league debut, Downs gave up
three runs on five hits in 6 1-3 innings against the Reds. ''I
thought he pitched excellent ball,'' manager Don Baylor said.
''Under the pressureof having all your family there, your first
major league game, he handled the pressure well.'' ... The Cubs
honored 1990s hits leader Mark Grace before the game. He was
presented with a flag that will fly above the field and his mother,
Sharon, threw out the first pitch. ''She's got a pretty good arm,
doesn't she?'' Grace said. ''I told her whatever you do, don't
bounce it.''
Reds-Rockies:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO--The Rockies, who have led the majors in attendance in
each of their seven seasons, drew 48,094. It was a club record for
opening day at Coors Field, and the 50,427 total tickets
distributed set a regular-season record. ... After the game, the
Rockies placed LF Jeffrey Hammonds on the 15-day disabled list,
retroactive to April 4, because of a strained right hamstring.
Taking Hammonds' place on the roster will be right-handed reliever
Rick Croushore, who will be recalled from Triple-A Colorado
Springs. ... Cirillo has five hits this season, all doubles. ...
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: 2B Pokey Reese, hit by a pitch on the left elbow,
left in the fifth inning with a bruise. ... The Reds signed LHP
Norm Charlton to a minor league contract. Charlton, who pitched for
the club from 1988-92, will report Wednesday to Triple-A
Louisville. ... Ochoa pulled his right hamstring in the ninth
inning. After hitting a dribbler, he injured himself running to
first, but Lee's throw was wild and Ochoa limped safely to first.
Diamondbacks-Padres:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: The Diamondbacks went from 3-9 against the Padres in
their expansion season of 1998 to 11-2 last year, including winning
5 of 6 in San Diego. ... Randy Johnson won't pitch this series, but
he might wish he did. Although the Padres beat him twice during the
1998 playoffs while he was with Houston, Johnson is 3-0 with a 1.91
ERA in four regular-season appearances against San Diego. ...
Former Padres CF Steve Finley, booed last year during his first
appearance back in San Diego, was cheered this time when the
Diamondbacks were introduced before the game.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: Ray, Bob and Bret Boone, from the first family to
have three generations of major leaguers, each threw out a
ceremonial first pitch. Bret Boone, the Padres' new second baseman,
was obtained in a December trade with Atlanta. His father and
grandfather both went to high school in San Diego. ... Former
public address announcer Bruce Binkowski, who didn't miss a game in
his 14 years at the mike, was honored during pre-game ceremonies.
He chose to step down to concentrate on his duties with the Holiday
Bowl. He will be promoted to executive director following this
year's Holiday Bowl. ... Manager Bruce Bochy expects CF Ruben
Rivera (ankle) back in the lineup Tuesday. ... Randy Myers, who
hasn't thrown a pitch since the 1998 World Series, was booed when
his name was called during the Padres' introductions. Myers, on the
disabled list following shoulder surgery last year, didn't run onto
the field.
Mets-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: The Phillies began a string of 14 straight games
against the NL East with Monday's home opener against the Mets. . .
Robin Roberts and Tug McGraw threw out the ceremonial first pitch.
. . Mickey Morandini, a fan favorite in Philly before getting
traded to the Cubs in December 1997, received a rousing ovation
upon his introduction. . . With Tuesday's off day, Phillies manager
Terry Francona is considering skipping No. 5 starter Chris Brock in
the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK -- Rickey Henderson, who said on Sunday he will not
speak to the media for a month, exchanged words during batting
practice with a heckler standing near the Phillies' dugout. . .
General manager Steve Phillips said he's not concerned with Todd
Zeile's slow start. ''People didn't think John Olerud would be able
to handle New York and he did as good a job as anybody,'' Phillips
said. . . Mike Piazza, a native of nearby Norristown, was besieged
by interview requests during pregame.
Cardinals-Astros:
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: The vintage locomotive that runs constantly in
pregame across a track atop a left field wall took the wise choice
and remained hidden during Cardinals' batting practice. Mark
McGwire sent four balls over the wall in left-center field and Eric
Davis sent two beyond the fence onto Crawford Street behind the
stadium. The train resumed its schedule after Cardinals BP. ...
Manager Tony La Russa likes the Cardinals' early surge but he's not
getting too excited. ''We have established a little something but
it's only the first week,'' La Russa said. ''We think we have a
chance to have a good ball club but that's as much as you can say
right now. The Astros feel the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: General manager Gerry Hunsicker didn't like what he saw
in the Astros clubhouse prior to Monday night's game: Three of his
stars, Jeff Bagwell, Craig Biggio and Ken Caminiti, were all on the
trainer's table. ''They were all curled up in the corner,''
Hunsicker said. Caminiti is out probably until Friday with a
hamstring pull. Bagwell and Biggio have a virus but started. ...
Daryle Ward went 0-for-4 Sunday and failed to get a run home in the
eighth that would have tied the game. Instead of giving his young
outfielder a rest, manager Larry Dierker started him in the cleanup
position against the Cardinals. ''Sometimes, you need to put a guy
right back out there, and without Caminiti in the lineup, we wanted
another left-handed bat in the lineup,'' Dierker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
