<HEADLINE> Hospital Workers Charged in Death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Three workers at a state hospital have
been charged with murder in the death of a patient who was
restrained after punching a hospital worker in the face, Attorney
General Mike Moore said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stem from the death of a 24-year-old patient
Saturday in a part of the hospital where violent, aggressive male
patients are housed. According to Mississippi State Hospital, the
patient was restrained for his own safety and then died after
choking on his own vomit.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said an autopsy performed on Kincharlsa Anderson led
investigators to believe the death was intentional. Moore did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital workers Curtis Branch, 23, Robert Thompson, 36, and
Jeffrey Sutton, 28, were arrested Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital director Bo Chastain called Anderson's death an
unfortunate event and said an internal investigation was underway.
He said the three workers were placed on administrative leave after
Anderson's death.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our employees at Mississippi State Hospital are very dedicated
to the tradition of safe care to our patients,'' Chastain said.
</P>
<P>
   The state hospital, just east of Jackson, has had a series of
patient-on-staff attacks the past several weeks. Three patients
have been charged in the incidents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
