<DOCNO> APW20000410.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 23:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Redskins Sign QB Jeff George  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH WHITE, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Washington Redskins purchased an expensive
insurance policy Monday, reaching an agreement with free agent
quarterback Jeff George on a four-year, $18.25 million contract to
back up Brad Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jeff was caught up in the idea of being with a Super Bowl
team,'' agent Leigh Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said a formal announcement would be made at Redskin
Park on Tuesday. Redskins director of player personnel Vinny
Cerrato did not return a call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Although the overall amount of money is astounding for a backup
quarterback, the contract is structured so that the Redskins and
George could easily sever ties after two years without a major dent
in the salary cap. If George is the starter by then, he would be
paid a handsome starter's salary -- $6 million per year over the
last two years of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   George began last season as the backup to Randall Cunningham in
Minnesota, but won the job after Cunningham struggled and went 9-3
as a starter. But the Vikings did not re-sign George, opting
instead to go with second-year quarterback Daunte Culpepper and
Bubby Brister after failing to convince Dan Marino not to retire.
</P>
<P>
   During his negotiations with Redskins owner Dan Snyder,
Steinberg used one of his other clients, Neil O'Donnell, as a
bargaining tool. O'Donnell went 4-1 for Super Bowl-bound Tennessee
last season after Steve McNair had back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ''For a team that wants to go to the Super Bowl, we noted in our
discussions that Neil O'Donnell played a critical role for the
Titans,'' Steinberg said. ''If Neil O'Donnell's not there, they
don't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said the agreement was concluded after talks Monday
evening with Snyder, who made it clear there will be no quarterback
controversy going into camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''Brad Johnson is the starter, but Jeff George is probably the
most amazing backup that is possible,'' Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The contract includes a $2 million signing bonus. George will
earn at least $500,000 the first year, but could get another $1
million if he gets enough playing time to meet certain incentives.
The base salaries for the following years are $3.75 million, $6
million and $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is reminiscent of the Redskins signing of Jeff
Hostetler in 1997. Hostetler was told he would be the backup, but
he openly questioned why he wasn't given a shot when Gus Frerotte
was struggling. Hostetler and the Redskins parted bitterly after
two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   George's initial thought appears to be that second-string is OK
if the team is championship contender.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm delighted to join the team with an incredible opportunity
to make a run for the Super Bowl,'' George said in a statement
released through Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   George, 32, a 10-year veteran, was the first pick in the 1990
draft and has played with Indianapolis, Atlanta, Oakland and last
year at Minnesota, where he started 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said it was the Vikings selection of Brister that
''heated up the talks with the Redskins.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said Snyder first floated the idea of wanting George
at the NFL owners meeting a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Daniel Snyder was a tremendously compelling salesman,'' he
said. ''He sort of put on a full court press.''
</P>
<P>
   George's signing continues a whirlwind Redskins offseason. Bruce
Smith and Mark Carrier were signed during the first week of free
agency, and Deion Sanders may join the team if the Cowboys cut him
in June, as expected. Washington also has the second and third
picks in this weekend's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dan Snyder reminds me of the early days of (Cowboys owner)
Jerry Jones, people who come in a with a fixed point of view and
want to succeed very quickly,'' Steinberg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-10-00 2303 </TRAILER>
